[White "Chapter 2 - 5...e5 6.de Nxe5"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B13"]
[Annotator "GM Arturs Neiksans"]
[PlyCount "39"]
[SourceVersionDate "2018.11.06"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 e5 $5 {I find it odd that this
logical move has been played so rarely - it is a pretty reasonable
continuation as Black fights for the centre. Although Black is trying to be
active, he voluntarily creates an isolated pawn - something that White can
press on for a very long time.} (5... Nf6 6. h3 e5 7. dxe5 Nxe5 8. Nf3 Nxd3+ 9.
Qxd3) 6. dxe5 Nxe5 7. Bb5+ {By far, the simplest and the best continuation
which promises White a small edge in all of the lines.} (7. Qe2 $5 {is a
tricky alternative that can be useful to know. Because of the simple f2-f4
threat to win a piece White forces Black to position the queen on the awkward
e7 square, slowing down his development. If Black plays it out accurately, he
should have a reasonable game, yet nowhere a full equality.} Qe7 8. Bb5+ Bd7 (
8... Nc6 9. Be3 $1 {[%csl Re7] a good try to cause Black some practical
problems - with the queens on the board Black has to be accurate with his
development. The motif might be available also in other lines as well.} Nf6 10.
h3 {[%cal Rf6g4,Rg4e3] a good prophylaxis against a future Nf6-g4 threat.} a6
11. Bd3 Ne5 {[%cal Re5d3,Re5c4]} 12. Nf3 {normally White would want to keep
his light-squared bishop but in case of a retreat Ne5-c4 was a serious threat.}
Nxd3+ 13. Qxd3 Qe4 14. Qd4 $1 Be7 15. Nbd2 Qxd4 16. Nxd4 O-O 17. O-O {White
can push this position forever - essentially he has a good knight vs a bad
bishop.}) 9. Bf4 $1 $146 {this logical move apparently is a novelty} (9. Bxd7+
{this most played move actually is an inaccuracy, as the practice already
shows!} Kxd7 $1 {[%cal Re5d3,Re5c4] a fantastic move which immediately gives
Black a great game. The two threats of Nd3+ and Nc4 are difficult to parry
simultaneously and as it happens, the "unsafe" placement of the black king is
irrelevant.} (9... Nxd7 10. Be3 Qe6 11. Nf3 Bc5 12. Nd4 Bxd4 13. Bxd4 Ne7 14.
Na3 $14 {probably is something that a White player would typically expect
after exchanging the bishops.}) 10. Qb5+ (10. Be3 Nc4 11. Nd2 Nxe3 12. fxe3 Re8
13. O-O-O Kc8 $11 {1-0 (43) Savic,M (2515)-Jovic,S (2313) Novi Sad 2017.})
10... Kc7 (10... Kc8 $5) 11. Bf4 g5 $1 12. Bxe5+ Qxe5+ 13. Ne2 Re8 {1-0 (53)
Nabaty,T (2654)-Lei,T (2514) Riga 2017. Doesn't look like an achievement for
White - the pin is very annoying.}) 9... Bxb5 {the most logical continuation
but Black has other options as well.} (9... O-O-O $5 10. Bxd7+ Nxd7 11. Nd2
Ngf6 {no matter what Black plays here, none of the continuations feel like full equality for him.} 12. Be3 (12. O-O-O $5 Qxe2 13. Nxe2 Bc5 14. f3 Rhe8 15.
Ng3 {[%cal Gd2b3,Gb3d4]}) 12... Qe6 13. Ngf3 Bc5 14. Nd4 Bxd4 15. Bxd4 Rhe8 16.
Qxe6 Rxe6+ (16... fxe6 17. f4 e5 18. fxe5 Nxe5 19. O-O-O {and Black doesn't
have a full equality, White's play is easier.}) 17. Kf1 Rde8 18. g3 Re2 19. Rd1
{[%cal Gd4e3]} R2e6 20. Kg2 $14) (9... Nf3+ $5 {it's a spectacular shot but
nothing much more.} 10. Kf1 $1 (10. Nxf3 Bxb5 11. Qxe7+ Nxe7 $1 12. Nd4 Bd7 13.
Nd2 Ng6 14. Bg3 f5 $1 $11 {[%cal Rf5f4]}) 10... Qxe2+ 11. Bxe2 Nxg1 {can you
imagine if you ever saw this position - how did the knight get on g1?} 12. Kxg1
Bc5 13. Nd2 Nf6 14. Nb3 Bb6 15. g3 {[%cal Gg1g2]} Ne4 16. Nd4 $14) 10. Qxb5+
Nc6+ 11. Ne2 Nf6 12. O-O Qd7 13. Nd2 Be7 14. Nf3 O-O 15. Rad1 {and White is
pressing.}) 7... Nc6 (7... Bd7 $6 {is not playable because after} 8. Qxd5 {
White has a healthy extra pawn.}) 8. Nf3 {the arising position has a lot of
resemblance with some lines in the French Defense (1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 3.Nd2 c5 4.
Ngf3 Nc6 5.exd5 exd5 6.Bb5 cxd4 and so on) thus if you're familiar with the
core ideas, they perfectly work also here. White's plan is to block the black
d-pawn at d4 and at the right time later - pressure it.} Nf6 {probably this is
the most reasonable continuation but Black might get cold feet regarding his
d5 pawn's well-being after Bc1-g5.} (8... Bc5 9. O-O Nge7 {might be another
way for Black to finish his development and take care of the annoying Bc1-g5
threat as now it's threatening nothing. However, the black knight on e7 feels
more passive than on f6 and it doesn't control the e4 square.} 10. Nbd2 a6 11.
Bd3 O-O 12. Nb3 {This is the standard placement of white pieces - White would
love to trade Black's dark-squared bishop if there's a possibility. It's also
important to note that with the black knight on e7 Black can't go Bc8-g4 in
one go because of a small tactical trick - Bxh7+ and Ng5+.} Bb6 {keeps at
least some temporal control of the d4 square but is not creating any threats.}
(12... Bd6 13. Re1 {Black is still not threatening with Bg4 so White has time
to make good and active moves. There's no need to rush with h2-h3 as Black
might opt for Bc8-f5 and then the h2-h3 move will feel like a waste of time.}
h6 14. h3 {now, of course, Bg4 is something that White should reckon with.} Bf5
15. Be3 $14) 13. Re1 {[%cal Gc1e3] There might be a scenario where White will
immediately go for Nbd4 or Nfd4 and then capture on d4 with a pawn in the end,
but in most occasions, it will simplify Black's defense. It's better to make
sure that the d4 square is occupied with a light piece.} h6 (13... Bg4 $2 14.
Bxh7+ Kxh7 15. Ng5+ Kg8 16. Qxg4) ({or} 13... Bf5 14. Be3 $14) 14. Be3 Bc7 15.
h3 {probably it's a good idea to limit Black's potential active ideas with
Bc8-g4 now that White no longer has the trick of Bxh7+} Bf5 16. Bc5 Bd6 17.
Bxf5 Nxf5 18. Qc2 Nfe7 19. Bxd6 Qxd6 20. Rad1 $14 {1-0 (41) Pavasovic,D (2495)
-Podkriznik,G (2295) Krsko 1997}) 9. O-O Be7 {a more careful move - now Bg5
makes little sense as it's not threatening with anything.} (9... Bc5 {is
seemingly more active but after} 10. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5f6,Gd1d5] White already
forces Black to be careful and after} Be6 (10... O-O 11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. Nbd2 Ne5
13. Nb3 Bb6 14. Re1 Bg4 15. Be2 Be6 16. Qd2 Kh8 17. Nbd4 Rg8 18. Nh4 Qf8 19. g3
$14 {1-0 (34) Smerdon,D (2470)-Van Tilbury,C (2280) Dresden 2008}) 11. Nd4 {
feels quite unpleasant for Black, for example,} Rc8 12. Bxc6+ $1 bxc6 13. Qe2
Qe7 (13... Bxd4 14. cxd4 O-O 15. Nc3 $14 {[%cal Gf2f3,Ga1c1,Gc3a4,Ga4c5]}) 14.
Re1 O-O 15. Nd2 {White has the better prospects.}) 10. Re1 (10. h3 O-O 11. Be3
Ne4 12. Nbd2 Bf5 13. Nd4 Nxd4 14. Bxd4 Bd6 15. Nf3 a6 16. Bd3 Re8 17. Re1 Bc7
18. c4 Re6 19. cxd5 Qxd5 20. Rc1 Qd6 21. Bc4 Re7 22. Be3 $14 {1/2-1/2 (45)
Lobanov, S (2239)-Yakubboev, N (2062) Al Ain 2013}) 10... O-O 11. h3 {not really
a mandatory move} (11. Bd3 Bg4 12. h3 Bh5 13. Be3 {[%cal Gb1d2] also looks
very much reasonable. Black might consider playing a quick Nf6-e4 and the
intimidating f7-f5 but will seriously weaken some of the central squares.})
11... Bf5 12. Be3 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gd2b3,Gb3d4] with a roughly equal game still I
would pick White. It's possible that Black could try to setup some kind of a
battery with Bd6-c7 and Qd6 but since it takes so long to build it, it can't
be very dangerous for White. A potential follow-up might be} a6 13. Bd3 Ne4 14.
Bc2 (14. Nbd2 $2 Nxf2 {[%cal Rf5d3]}) 14... Bg6 15. Nbd2 f5 (15... Re8 16. Nxe4
$5 (16. Nd4) 16... dxe4 17. Nd2 {[%csl Rb6][%cal Gd2c4,Gd1g4]}) 16. Qe2 Qc7 17.
Rad1 {[%cal Gf3d4]} Bf6 18. Nxe4 dxe4 19. Ng5 Bxg5 20. Bxg5 {White should be
better due to the bishop pair, as long as he doesn't allow Black to play f5-f4
without consequences.} *

