{[%evp 0,43,19,20,72,76,58,66,66,24,30,27,50,50,45,10,3,3,3,2,18,18,18,11,14,0,
3,-10,0,-7,3,9,8,-6,8,-3,-3,-18,19,9,15,26,30,30,30,51]} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3.
exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Qc7 {one of the two main moves in this position -
Black stops the immediate Bf4 from happening and keeps various position setups
available for him.} 6. Ne2 {[%cal Gc1f4] White insists on making Bf4 possible
at the expense of the slightly misplaced knight on e2. From Chapter 4 to 6 I
will cover the three main setups and how to meet them.} (6. Nf3 {the problem
of this move lies with the fact that after} Bg4 $11 {[%cal Re7e6,Rg8f6] Black
will continue normal development and after h2-h3 can safely retreat to h5 and
later to g6. It doesn't mean this position is not playable, just that Black
has an excellent position.}) (6. Na3 $5 {there have been some attempts to win
a tempo by forcing Black to play a7-a6 but it's not clear if the knight later
on c2-e3 will be contributing more than on d2-f3.} a6 7. Nc2 Nf6 8. h3 $5 (8.
Ne2 Bg4 9. f3 Bd7 10. Bf4 e5 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. O-O Bd6 {looks rather harmless
for Black}) 8... e6 9. Nf3 b5 10. O-O Bb7 11. Re1 Bd6 $13 {0-1 (29) Kramnik,V 
(2812) -Fedoseev,V (2726) Dortmund 2017}) (6. h3 {for some time I was
considering this old move to be a good approach for White and a good weapon in
practical games until I started to get a better picture of the entire
Caro-Kann Karlsbad structure and that's when I realized that after} Nf6 7. Nf3
g6 8. O-O Bf5 $1 {this is simply too good for Black.} 9. Bxf5 gxf5 10. Re1 e6 {
[%cal Rf8d6,Re8c8] The positional drawbacks are obvious - White has already
castled short, h2-h3 is a useless and a weakening move of the white king, and
Black hasn't even played Bg7 and can opt for a long castle instead.}) 6... e6 {
[%cal Rf8d6,Rg8e7,Rf7f6] We'll start with this slightly rare and by the looks
- passive move. Things are not so simple as Black wants to play Bd6, Nge7 and
in the near future prepare f7-f6 and e6-e5.} (6... Bg4 {will be covered in
Chapter 5 and 6.}) (6... Nf6 $6 {makes no sense as now White develops the
bishop with a tempo and the queen has to retreat.} 7. Bf4 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gd2f3]}
Qb6 8. Qb3 $14) (6... e5 {similar as in Chapter 2, also here Black can opt for
the quick breakthrough in the centre which will leave him with an isolated
pawn.} 7. dxe5 Nxe5 8. Bb5+ Bd7 9. Bxd7+ (9. Qxd5 {is too risky because Black
gains initiative with} O-O-O $44) 9... Qxd7 10. Bf4 Ng6 11. O-O {[%cal Gb1d2,
Gd2f3] and White will be pushing for a long time with a small but comfortable
edge.}) 7. Bf4 {in general White should be happy to trade off the dark-squared
bishops, especially if it comes together with winning a tempo.} Bd6 8. Bxd6
Qxd6 9. O-O {the order of the next two White moves probably doesn't matter,
either playing Nd2 or castle first.} Nge7 10. Nd2 O-O {most likely Black has
to make a short castle albeit castling long can be an interesting way to
provoke hostilities.} (10... Bd7 11. f4 O-O-O $146 {so far, nobody dared to
try this} 12. b4 Nf5 13. Qc1 $36 {[%cal Gd2b3,Ga2a4,Gb3c5] White has better
prospects to start a dangerous attack. If Black will launch h7-h6 and g7-g5,
most likely White can just ignore it and focus on the queenside.}) 11. f4 $5 {
[%cal Gd2f3] A very principled continuation to fight for the centre, slow down
Black's plans for f7-f6 and e6-e5 and eye for a potential kingside attack.
This will either lead Black to a game with an isolated pawn on d5, or he can
opt for f7-f5 and reroute his knight from e7 to e4.} (11. Ng3 {[%cal Gd2f3,
Gd3c2,Gd1d3,Gh2h5] An interesting alternative for a couple of tries. Typically
the white knights go on f3 and g3, and with the help of the queen + bishop
battery, bother Black with h2-h4-h5. However, I failed to find a good plan for
White, should Black immediately play f7-f6 and e6-e5.} f6 $1 $146 {[%cal Re6e5]
with clear intentions to play e6-e5 and guarding the h7 pawn with h7-h6 if
necessary. After other continuations, I managed to convince myself that White
can fight for an advantage.} (11... e5 {Black can force matters in the centre
but not necessarily this gives him equality.} 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nb3 $5 (13. Nc4
$5 {a spectacular shot but perhaps it's not required. In general White should
be concentrating on occupying the d4 square with one of his knights.} Nxc4 (
13... dxc4 $4 14. Bxh7+ Kxh7 15. Qxd6 {is usually a warm-up combination in
textbooks.}) 14. Bxc4 Be6 15. Bb3 Rfd8 16. Ne2 Nc6 17. Re1 (17. Nd4 $5 Qc5 18.
Nxe6 fxe6 19. Qg4 Rd6 20. Rae1 e5 {[%cal Ge1e3,Gh2h5,Gb3c2] and here comes the
eternal question of GMs - is this enough for White to claim an advantage?
White's chances still seem better as he can start an inspired kingside attack.}
) 17... d4 $5 18. Bxe6 fxe6 19. Nxd4 Nxd4 20. cxd4 Qxd4 21. Qb3 Qd5 22. Rxe6
Qxb3 23. axb3 Rd2 24. Re7 $14 {1/2-1/2 (37) Praggnanandhaa,R (2520)-Nikolaidis,
I (2535) Heraklion 2018}) 13... N7c6 14. Be2 Rd8 {[%cal Rd5d4] Black is
threatening to exhange his weakness} 15. Qc2 Be6 (15... d4 {would be playing
with fire} 16. cxd4 Nxd4 17. Nxd4 Qxd4 18. Rad1 Qb6 19. Rxd8+ Qxd8 20. Rd1 Qe7
21. Qe4 g6 22. Bc4 $14) 16. Rad1 Qc7 17. Rfe1 {and White is going to be
pressing for a long time. Ideally the g3 knight should land on d4.}) (11... Ng6
12. Re1 $146 {Black might get to play f7-f6 and e6-e5 but White has not made
any commital decisions and he can hope to press on Black's freshly created
weaknesses. For example,} f6 (12... Bd7 13. Nf3 a5 14. Bc2 {[%cal Gd1d3,Gh2h5]}
) 13. Qc2 Nce7 14. Rad1 {[%cal Gd2f3,Gh2h5]} Bd7 (14... e5 $6 15. dxe5 fxe5 16.
Nc4 Qe6 17. Bxg6 Nxg6 18. Ne3 Rd8 19. Qb3 Ne7 (19... Nf4 20. Ne2) 20. f4 $16)
15. Nf3 (15. Ndf1 Rac8 16. Ne3 Be8 17. Ne2 Bf7 18. Qd2 Rfd8 19. Bc2 {[%cal
Gc2b3,Gc3c4] with a lot of maneuvering included, most likely White's only
chance to open the position is with c3-c4. If Black would try to stop it with
b7-b5, this would seriously weaken the c5 square that White can invade with a
maneuver Nd3-c5 and strenghten with b2-b4. The position is roughly balanced.})
15... Kh8 16. Qd2 {rearranging the placement of the bishop and the queen for
the battery can be a great idea.} Rac8 17. Bc2 a5 18. h4 Nf4 19. Ne2 Neg6 20.
Nxf4 Qxf4 21. Re3 $14 {[%cal Gg2g3] White has an easier game and options to
target the Black king.}) 12. Re1 {e6-e5 is inevitable - White should get ready
to counter it.} (12. f4 {it is possible that White will have to consider this
move and play it anyway. By doing this, later on Black can switch to the f6-f5
idea and move a knight to e4.}) 12... e5 (12... Bd7 13. Nf3 e5 (13... Rae8 14.
Bc2) 14. dxe5 fxe5 15. b4 a6 16. a4 Bg4 17. Bxh7+ Kh8 18. Bd3 Bxf3 19. gxf3 Qf6
20. Bc2 Qxf3 21. Qxf3 Rxf3 22. b5 axb5 23. axb5 Rxa1 24. Rxa1 Nd8 25. Ra8 Rf8
26. Rb8 $14 {[%cal Gc2b3]}) 13. dxe5 fxe5 14. c4 Be6 15. cxd5 Nxd5 {Black has
an isolated pawn on e5 which is something that White can target, but at the
same time he's very active.} 16. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3g5,Gd3c2]} Rad8 17. Ng5 h6 18.
N3e4 Qe7 19. Nxe6 Qxe6 20. Rc1 Nd4 $11) 11... Bd7 {[%cal Rf7f6,Rd7e8,Re8g6]
with a typical French defense idea - in the next few moves Black might play
f7-f6 and either threaten with e6-e5, or rearrange the bishop to e8 and g6.
It's in White's best interest to stop the latter idea otherwise Black will get
an excellent game.} (11... Nf5 {[%cal Rd6c7,Rf5d6,Rf7f5,Rd6e4] this probably
signals that Black is opting for the rerouting of the knight on e5 and that he
will play f7-f5 real soon. Let's not forget about the fork on e3 as well!} 12.
Qe1 Qc7 (12... Bd7 13. Qf2 Rae8 14. Nf3 f6 15. Kh1 a6 {with the obvious idea
to play e6-e5 next move} (15... e5 {probably is playable but it can be
difficult to evaluate the consequences afterwards} 16. dxe5 fxe5 17. fxe5 Nxe5
18. Nxe5 Qxe5 19. Qxa7 Ne3 20. Rxf8+ Rxf8 21. Ng3 Bc6 22. Re1 d4 23. Qxd4 Qxd4
24. cxd4 Nxg2 25. Re7 Nf4+ 26. Be4 {Black is down a pawn, but close to
equality.}) 16. g4 Nfe7 (16... Nh6 17. g5 fxg5 18. Nxg5 Nf5 19. Rg1 {[%csl Ge5]
should be in White's favor.}) 17. Qh4 Ng6 18. Qh5 Re7 (18... Nce7 19. Rae1 {
[%cal Gf4f5] albeit better, this leaves Black in a passive defense as Black
can forget about playing e6-e5.}) 19. Nh4 $1 f5 20. Nxg6 hxg6 21. Qxg6 $16 {
1-0 (30) Ganguly,S (2638)-Le Roux,J (2533) chess.com INT 2019}) 13. Nf3 {
comes together with a little trick} (13. g4 $5 {can lead to a sharp game if
both players are up for it.} Ne3 {a very principled reply but still not
mandatory} (13... Nd6 14. Nf3 f5 15. Ng3 Ne4 16. Qe3 {[%cal Gg4f5,Gf3e5,Gg1h1,
Gf1g1] White probably will exchange the pawns on f5, play Ne5 and organize an
offensive at the g-file.}) 14. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 15. Qh4+ Kg8 16. Rf3 {[%cal Gf3h3]
} Nxg4 (16... Nc4 {according to the engines, this is a draw everywhere but the
game can be very wild. Just a sample of the lines:} 17. Nxc4 dxc4 18. g5 $1 Ne7
(18... e5 19. f5 Bxf5 20. Rxf5 exd4 21. Rf3) 19. Rh3 f6 20. Qh7+ Kf7 21. gxf6
Kxf6 22. Re1 Kf7 23. Qh5+ g6 24. Qg5 Ke8 25. Rh7 Rf7 26. Rh8+ Kd7 27. d5 $1
Qc5+ 28. Nd4 Rf5 29. dxe6+ Kc7 $13) 17. Qxg4 Ne7 18. Nf1 {with good attacking
perspectives as the black king is weakened.}) 13... f6 {Black is cautious - he
is fine to waste a tempo for the knight's rerouting on d6 and play f6-f5
afterwards.} (13... Nd6 $2 14. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 15. Ng5+ Kg8 (15... Kg6 16. f5+ $3
{[%csl Rc7][%cal Ge2f4]} Nxf5 17. Rxf5 $3 exf5 18. Qh4 $18 {[%cal Ge2f4]}) 16.
Qh4 Re8 17. f5 $1 Nxf5 18. Qh7+ Kf8 19. Rae1 {[%cal Ge2g3] with a deadly attack
}) 14. Kh1 {It's probably a good idea to include this move sooner or later as
the need to open the g-file for an attack might arise, move the king in the
corner to avoid any checks should Black open the center, plus Black could try
to force a perpetual attack for the rook with Ne3-g4.} Nd6 15. Ng3 f5 16. Qe3
Ne4 17. a3 {[%cal Gc3c4,Ga1c1] as explained elsewhere, in the situation when
Black has landed with a knight on e4, strengthened by the d5 and f5 pawns, the
