pawn majority at the queenside with b2-b4 and c4-c5.}) 12. Nf3 {Now Black has
to choose which approach to play.} (12. Qe1 {also has decent logic.} f6 13. Qg3
Rae8 (13... Be8 14. Rae1 Bg6 $6 15. Bxg6 Nxg6 16. f5 $1 Qxg3 17. Nxg3 exf5 18.
Nxf5 $14 {[%csl Rd5,Rg6]}) 14. Rae1 Nd8 15. Nb3 b6 16. Kh1 Nf7 17. Ng1 Nf5 18.
Qh3 N5h6 19. Qg3 Qc7 20. Nd2 Nd6 21. Qf3 f5 22. Qe2 Ne4 23. Ngf3 Nf7 24. Ne5 $6
Nxe5 25. fxe5 Qd8 26. Kg1 Re7 27. Nxe4 $6 dxe4 28. Bc2 Bc6 29. Rd1 b5 30. b3
Rd7 31. g3 Qb6 32. Qf2 Bd5 33. Rfe1 Rc7 34. Re3 Rfc8 35. Qd2 Qa5 36. b4 Qxa2 {
0-1 (36) David,A (2563)-Rodshtein,M (2678) Brest 2018}) 12... f6 {since Black
is still threatening to play Be8-g6, White should take care of it first.} (
12... Nf5 13. Qd2 Qc7 14. g4 Nd6 15. Ng3 f5 16. g5 Ne4 17. Qe3 {the fate of
this line depends on how White can play out this position. White's position
seems to be slightly better - he has the better bishop and some chances for a
direct attack against the black king. However, it's important not to rush it.
Probably White should be happy to get a position with a knight against the
supposedly bad bishop, either the knight standing or e5, or after the trade -
on d4. For example,} a6 18. Ne2 b5 19. a3 Rab8 20. Ne5 Nxe5 21. dxe5 a5 22. Nd4
) 13. Qc2 {Now Black has to make a commital decision.} (13. Qd2 Be8 14. Rae1
Bg6 $11) 13... g6 {the safe move but now the black bishop will never get to g6.
As far as I can see, White here has three options: 1) A well-prepared g2-g4-g5
might be an interesting idea to consider, fighting for the control of the e5
square. However, White should consider that Black can counterstrike in the
center with e6-e5.2) Prepare b2-b3 and c3-c4, fighting for a strong pawn
center. Black's pieces feel positioned really clumsy. 3) Improve the
positioning of the pieces and try to provoke Black for more weaknesses. White
should be ready that Black can play e6-e5 at any moment. This will leave him
with an isolated pawn, so the circumstances and additional positional factors
will be important.} (13... Nf5 {seems to be a risky choice which already has
been tested in a spectacular game.} 14. g4 $1 {accepting the thrown gauntlet} (
