14. Rae1 Rae8 15. Ng3 Kh8 16. Qd2 $14 {[%cal Gf3h4,Gd3b1,Gd2d3] Most likely
Black will play at some point f6-f5 anyway and switch to the plan bringing a
knight to e4.}) 14. Qd2 Rae8 15. Rae1 Qc7 16. b3 {[%cal Gc3c4] I'm not sure
how critical is this particular position as both sides had plenty of ways to
divert earlier. Either way, it seems that the only reasonable way for White to
get a clear plan is to play c3-c4 at the right time. Perhaps it's a better
idea to maneuver first and improve the piece placement to the maximum, allow
the Black knight to land on e4, strengthened by the d5 and f5 pawns and only
then prepare c3-c4 as Black won't be able to capture the pawn without serious
positional consequences. Ideally White wants to create a protected passed pawn
at the queenside with c3-c4-c5, strengthened with b3-b4. Of course, White has
to anticipate Black's countermeasures b7-b6 or e6-e5 at any given time.} (16.
g4 Nc8 17. Ng3 Nd6 18. g5 f5 19. Ne5 Nxe5 20. Rxe5 {1/2-1/2 (42) Terletsky,O 
(2263)-Punin,A (2259) Lvov 2016}) 16... Nf5 17. c4 dxc4 18. bxc4 Na5 19. Rc1 b6
20. g4 Nh6 21. h3 Nf7 22. Ng3 {with a complex middlegame and chances for both
sides.} *

