his development.} Bd6 14. g3 Qb6 $1 {again, very accurate. Black slows down
White's development.} 15. Rf2 Kf8 $1 16. Kg2 {[%cal Rb6g1] a part of
rearranging the pieces - the king on g2 stands well to avoid any potential
tactical tricks after Nxd4 or e6-e5.} f5 {[%cal Rc6e7,Re7g8,Rg8f6] Black is
rerouting his knight to e4.} 17. Rc2 {otherwise it's difficult to develop the
queenside without making commital weaknesses.} Ne7 18. Nd2 Ng8 19. Qe2 {
time to go! Now the only viable plan for White is to prepare c3-c4.} Nf6 20.
Nf3 h5 21. Rf1 {last preparation} (21. b3 h4 $1 22. Nxh4 Bxf4 {White should be
ready for this}) 21... Kg7 22. b3 Be7 23. c4 $13 {[%cal Gc4d5,Gd3c4,Ra8g8,
Rh5h4] I'm not sure how to properly evaluate this position. Obviously White is
advancing pawns at the queenside and can either try to form a passed pawn with
c4-c5 and b3-b4-b5, or capture on d5, followed by Bc4 and if the knight
retreats - d4-d5. Perhaps the latter choice is safer and more direct. At the
same time Black is dreaming about h5-h4 and can start an improvized attack at
some time with Rag8, Kf8 and h5-h4. So my most honest evaluation probably is -
it's equal with chances for both sides. Black picked up a lot of the absolute
best moves to get here. If you don't like the position, there are number of
ways to surprise your opponent with the sidelines, presented in this chapter.}
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 6 - 5...Qc7, 8...Bxe2"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B13"]
[Annotator "GM Arturs Neiksans"]
[PlyCount "43"]
[SourceVersionDate "2018.11.06"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Qc7 6. Ne2 Bg4 7. O-O e6 8. Qe1
Bxe2 {the safest choice - since White has several tricks in his arsenal to
choose from, Black can voluntarily give up his light-squared bishop to get an
easier to play position. The alternatives are covered in other chapters.  This
setup can arise from many lines with slight differences. Sometimes Black will
have already included a7-a6, sometimes the white f-pawn already will be
standing on f4. I believe that the typical ideas don't change so you can
recognize them already from afar.} (8... Nf6 9. Bg5 Bxe2 10. Qxe2 Bd6 11. g3 {
should be something similar, except the white bishop is already on g5.}) 9.
Qxe2 Bd6 10. g3 {So far I believe everything is almost forced - White could
have played f2-f4 immediately but afterwards you will be obliged to play g2-g3
anyway in order to develop your knight with Nb1-d2-f3. As far as I can see it,
Black has two real options here:  1) Play Nf6 and proceed with a short castle.
Afterwards, he either aims for the breakthrough in the centre with e6-e5 or to
try to create some weaknesses at the queenside, by executing the typical idea
b7-b5, a7-a5, b5-b4 and target the c3 pawn.  2) Play long castle and hope for
an attack at the kingside with the standard h7-h5-h4.} Nf6 11. Nd2 O-O {
Let's check the Black's plan No.1 - he plays it safe and opts for a positional
approach. Here White has two options: either go for the aggressive f4-f4 which
is pretty much straightforward but it gives up the e4 square forever, or aim
for more positional manoeuvring with Nf3 -> Bg5 etc.} (11... h5 12. Nf3 {
the way I treat the position, the immediate h5-h4 gives Black too good
position so probably it's a great idea to stop it, at least for the time being.
} (12. f4 $5 {I played this once myself - it's quite provocative as White
doesn't manage to stop the incoming h5-h4, the engines think it's equal
somewhere but it can lead to some entertaining lines. Probably the main line
is simply better.} h4 13. Nf3 hxg3 14. hxg3 O-O-O 15. Kg2 Ne7 (15... Ng4 $1 {
[%cal Rg7g5]} 16. Rh1 (16. Nh4 $6 Nh2 $3 {[%cal Rg7g5]} 17. Rh1 g5 18. Ng6 fxg6
19. Qxe6+ Kb8 20. Rxh2 Rxh2+ 21. Kxh2 gxf4 22. Kg2 Ka8 $17) 16... Rxh1 17. Kxh1
Rh8+ 18. Kg1 (18. Kg2 $2 g5 {[%cal Rd6g3,Rh8h2]}) 18... Ne7 19. Ng5 (19. Ne5 {
0-1 (48) Martinez Alfonso,J (2034)-Avila Jimenez,X (2159) Vilafranca del
Penedes 2019}) 19... Nh6 20. Bd2) 16. Bd2 Nf5 17. Ne5 {[%cal Gf1h1]} Nh5 18.
Be1 {from afar it looks risky but Black has a hard time to make any good out
of this.} g6 19. Rh1 Rh7 20. Qf3 Rdh8 21. Bf2 $14 f6 $4 22. Nxg6 Nhxg3 23. Bxg3
Rxh1 24. Rxh1 Rxh1 25. Bxf5 Rc1 26. Qe3 {1-0 (26) Neiksans,A (2559)-Starostits,
I (2457) Riga 2019}) 12... O-O-O $6 {The plan No.2 - Black tries to hide his
king at the queenside so that he can focus attacking at the kingside. I think
this is a very risky approach and can backfire badly. Then again - if Black
decides to stay in the centre or transfer the king to g7, it remains unclear -
why did he play h7-h5 in the first place.} 13. a4 {[%cal Ga4a5] A very easy
plan - a quick march forward with the a-pawn and a direct attack at the
queenside. The dark-squared bishops remain on c1, at least for the time being.
} Rde8 {[%cal Re6e5] it makes sense to answer a queenside attack with a
counter-strike in the centre.} (13... h4 $6 {is interesting but the engines
are not really impressed} 14. Nxh4 Rxh4 15. gxh4 Rh8 16. Bg5 Bxh2+ 17. Kg2 Nh5
18. Rh1 Bf4 19. Qf3 $16 f6 $6 20. Bg6 $1 {[%csl Rh5]}) (13... Kb8 {hiding the
king in the corner is a reasonable idea but it costs time. White can proceed
with the same idea.} 14. a5 Nxa5 15. Bg5 {[%cal Ga1a4,Gf1a1] here the
immediate b2-b4 doesn't work as Black has protected his a7 pawn. Ultimately
the plan doesn't change - pressure the a-file with the heavy artillery.} Rc8
16. Ra4 Nc4 17. Rfa1 a6 18. Bxc4 dxc4 19. Nd2 Nd5 20. Nxc4 h4 21. Nxd6 Qxd6 22.
c4 hxg3 23. fxg3 f6 24. Bd2 Nc7 25. Rb4 Ka8 26. Qf3 $16 {the black king is in
the heavy crossfire.}) 14. a5 $1 {a common idea, borrowed from the Sicilian
Dragon line - White sacrifices a pawn to accelerate his attack at the
queenside.} Nxa5 {Sure, it's risky but what else?} (14... e5 15. dxe5 Bxe5 16.
Nxe5 Nxe5 17. a6 b6 18. Bf5+ Nfd7 19. h4 g6 20. Bh3 f5 21. Bg2 Nf6 22. Bf4 $16)
(14... a6 15. b4 e5 16. dxe5 Nxe5 17. b5 $40 {looks even worse for Black}) 15.
b4 {[%csl Ra7] if the a7 pawn would be protected, then this wouldn't work. An
alternative is Bg5, R1a4 and Rfa1.} Nc6 16. Ba3 (16. Bg5 {also looks great.})
16... Kb8 (16... Ne7 17. b5 Bxa3 18. Rxa3 Kb8 19. b6 $1 {opening more lines}
Qxb6 20. Ne5 $16 {[%csl Rb8][%cal Gf1b1,Ge5f7]}) 17. b5 Ne7 18. b6 $1 Qxb6 19.
Rfb1 Qc7 20. Bxd6 Qxd6 21. Ne5 Rhf8 22. Ba6 b6 23. Bb7 $3 {[%cal Ge2a6,Ga6a7]
it's not a forced but it nicely illustrates the storm that White can conjure
at the queenside. Notice how Black didn't even start his offensive at the
kingside.}) 12. f4 {[%cal Gd2f3,Gf3e5,Gf3g5] White stops the e6-e5 from ever
happening and intends to start a full-scale assault at the kingside. The way I
see it, Black has two options - either stop the attack with the pretty much
inevitable f7-f5 and reroute a knight to e4, or have cold steel nerves and
proceed with a counter-attack at the queenside. For an engine it might be the
best choice, however human beings usually fear of an incoming attack.} (12. Nf3
{[%cal Gc1g5,Gf1e1,Ga1d1] with this approach White doesn't rush with closing
the center and thus - permanently weakening the e4 square. White intends to
provoke some weaknesses from Black's side first, and eye for a kingside attack.
Black can play e6-e5 but this will lead to positions with an isolated pawn on
d5. I'll present to you a couple of games which will give you a better
understanding how usually White plays from here.} a6 (12... Rfe8 13. Be3 {
White doesn't mind if Black will play e6-e5.} g6 (13... e5 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15.
Nxe5 Bxe5 16. Qf3 $14 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Ga1d1,Gf1e1]}) 14. Rad1 a6 15. a3 b5 16.
Rfe1 Na5 17. Bg5 Nd7 18. Ne5 (18. h4 $5 {[%cal Gh4h5]}) 18... Nc4 19. Ng4 f5
20. Ne3 Nxe3 21. Qxe3 Nb6 22. Qf3 Nc4 23. Re2 Qf7 24. Rde1 Rac8 25. h4 Bf8 26.
Kg2 h5 27. Qf4 $14 {1-0 (79) Delgado Ramirez,N (2613)-Erenburg,S (2550)
Medellin 2017}) 13. Bg5 Nd7 14. Rad1 b5 15. Rfe1 Na5 (15... Rfe8 16. Bb1 Rac8
17. Qd3 Nf8 18. Kg2 b4 19. c4 {a common idea to switch to a game with an
isolated pawn on d4, however White has two bishop and some space advantage.}
dxc4 20. Qxc4 Qa5 21. Qe2 h6 22. Bc1 Ne7 23. Ne5 Bxe5 24. dxe5 Red8 25. Rxd8
Rxd8 26. h4 Nf5 27. h5 $14 {1/2-1/2 (46) Heberla,B (2570)-Carow,J (2437)
Karlsruhe 2018}) 16. Ne5 Nxe5 17. dxe5 Be7 18. Bf6 $1 {a nice motif to know!}
g6 (18... gxf6 19. Qg4+ $1 Kh8 20. exf6 Bxf6 21. Qh5 $18) 19. Qg4 Rfe8 20. Qh4
Nc6 21. Re3 Bxf6 22. exf6 Qd6 23. Bxg6 $1 fxg6 24. f7+ Kg7 25. fxe8=N+ Rxe8 26.
Qg4 b4 27. cxb4 d4 28. Qe4 e5 29. a3 {1-0 (29) Ragger,M (2644)-Vogel,R (2477)
Czech Republic 2018}) 12... a6 (12... Rae8 {[%csl Ge6][%cal Rf6d7,Rf7f5,Rd7f6,
Rf6e4] clearly an indication that Black will prepare f7-f5 as the other rook
is left on f8. There's nothing White can do about it, so focus on improving
your pieces.} 13. Nf3 Nd7 14. Be3 $146 {it makes more sense to position the
bishop on e3. It doesn't do much there at the moment, but it solidifies
White's position around it even more.} (14. Bd2 f5 15. Ne5 Nf6 16. Kh1 Ne4 17.
Be3 a6 18. Rg1 Bxe5 19. fxe5 Qf7 20. Raf1 h5 21. c4 dxc4 22. Bxe4 Qd7 23. Bg2
b5 24. Qxh5 Nb4 25. Rd1 Nd3 26. Qe2 Rc8 27. Rgf1 Nb4 28. a3 Nd5 29. Bd2 Rfd8
30. Ba5 Re8 31. Bb4 Qf7 32. Bxd5 exd5 33. Qf3 g6 34. g4 {1-0 (34) Yu,Y (2729)
-Dreev,A (2652) Doha 2016}) 14... f5 {Obviously, Black doesn't have to rush
with it, but I imagine it's difficult for Black to progress without it. As
soon as Black plays f7-f5, preparing to reroute the black knight to e4, White
can either push c3-c4, or opt for a kingside attack at the g-file.} 15. c4 {
with an idea to either go forward with c4-c5 and create a passed pawn at the
queenside, or take on d5, followed by Nf3-e5.} (15. Kh1 $5 Nf6 16. Rg1 a6 17.
Ne5 Ne4 18. Rg2 {I'd like to point it out that White can ignore the knight on
e4 for quite some time as it's not doing much.} Kh8 19. Rag1 {[%cal Gg3g4]}
Nxe5 20. fxe5 Be7 21. Rf1 $14 {[%cal Gg3g4,Gc3c4]}) 15... dxc4 (15... Nf6 16.
Rac1 Qe7 17. c5 Bc7 18. a3 $14 {[%cal Gb2b5]}) 16. Bxc4 Nb6 17. Bb3 Na5 18.
Rac1 Qd7 19. Bc2 Nd5 20. Bd3 a6 21. Bf2 $14 {[%csl Re6] Despite the fact that
Black has a nice outpost on d5 for his knight, his pawn on e6 is eternally
weak. White seems to be pushing.}) (12... Rfe8 13. Nf3 Nd7 14. Bd2 (14. Be3 $5
{[%cal Ga1e1]}) 14... a6 15. Rae1 Na5 16. b3 $5 {a very interesting approach
to stop Black's ideas at the queenside - this is why the bishop was positioned
at d2.} (16. Ne5 {[%cal Gd3h7,Ge2h5,Gh5f7]} Nf8 17. g4 b5 18. g5 Nc4 19. Bc1 {
[%cal Gf1f3,Gf3h3] to me the White's attack looks very much real.}) 16... b5
17. Ne5 Nf8 18. Qg2 Rad8 19. Re2 Qb6 20. Qf2 f6 21. Nf3 Nc6 22. b4 Re7 23. Kh1
Nd7 24. Qg2 Qc7 25. Rfe1 Rde8 26. Nh4 Nb6 27. Qh3 f5 28. Nf3 Nd8 29. Ne5 Nc4
30. Bc1 Nb6 31. g4 Bxe5 32. dxe5 g6 33. Be3 Na4 34. Rc2 fxg4 35. Qxg4 Rg7 36.
Rg1 Nc6 37. h4 Qf7 38. Rcg2 $16 {1-0 (73) Tari,A (2595)-Arat,U (2400) Kocaeli
2017}) 13. Nf3 b5 {[%cal Rb5b4] Black is eyeing for a quick b5-b4, creating
some targets at the queenside.} 14. a3 {I think the rule here is as follows -
if by playing a2-a3 you force Black to spend several tempos to prepare a6-a5
and b5-b4, go for it. Time is of the essence.} Ne7 15. Bd2 {[%cal Ga1e1] a
strange move but it's necessary to connect both rooks and also protect the e4
square with an additional piece. The dark-squared bishop at the moment doesn't
play a critical role.} Qb7 $1 {[%cal Rf6e4,Ra6a5,Rb5b4] one of the key ideas
for Black - he wants to play Ne4 and strengthen it with f7-f5. I imagine that
at this point it's in White's interest to stop it.} 16. Rae1 {just in time}
Rab8 {[%csl Gd3,Ge2][%cal Gd3b5] one of the perks for White having the bishop
on d3 and queen on e2 - it heavily slows down the b5-b4 maneuver.} 17. Ne5 {
[%cal Gg3g4,Gf4f5] preparing to move forward with the kingside pawns.} (17. Ng5
Qd7 18. g4 a5 19. b4 axb4 20. axb4 h6 21. Nh3 Ne4 $1 22. Bxe4 dxe4 23. Qxe4
Rfe8 $44 {1/2-1/2 (52) Le,Q (2715)-Nisipeanu,L (2661) Batumi 2018}) 17... a5
18. g4 (18. b4 {[%csl Rb5] depending on the situation, b2-b4 is a very common
idea in these lines. White stops b5-b4 from happening and fixes a weakness on
b5, while the pawn on c3 is protected. However, please be advised that Black
has a nice positional sacrifice at his disposal.} axb4 19. axb4 Ne4 $1 20. Bxe4
dxe4 21. Qxe4 Qxe4 22. Rxe4 Ra8 {[%cal Re7d5,Rf8c8,Ra8a2] Black has an
excellent compensation for the pawn.}) 18... b4 19. axb4 axb4 20. f5 $1 (20. g5
{would again run into the pawn sacrifice.} Ne4 $1 21. Bxe4 dxe4 22. Qxe4 Qxe4
23. Rxe4 bxc3 24. bxc3 Rfc8) 20... bxc3 21. bxc3 exf5 (21... Bxe5 22. Qxe5 $1
Nxg4 23. Qe2 Nf6 24. fxe6 $16) 22. gxf5 $14 {[%csl Gd2,Gd3,Rg7][%cal Gg1h1,
Gf1g1,Rb8b2,Rb7c7,Ge5g4] White's chances look better as he has an open g-file
for an attack and all of his pieces are ready to join it. It would be wise to
watch out for Black to play the typical Rb8-b2, causing some annoying pins.} *

