1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 {finally we've come to the
two knights variation where Black doesn't stop White's Bf4 from being played.}
6. Bf4 (6. Ne2 $5 {as an element of surprise, it's possible also here to
employ the same idea, explored in Chapter 5.} e5 {probably the most tempting
move as White didn't stop it from happening.} (6... Bg4 7. O-O e6 8. Qe1 {
Comparing with the main line of Chapter 5, the biggest drawback is that Black
doesn't have to "waste" a tempo on Qc7.} Bd6 (8... Bh5 9. Nf4 Bg6 10. Nxg6 hxg6
11. Qe2 Bd6 12. g3 {now we've seen this position somewhere!}) 9. Ng3 O-O (9...
Nh5 10. Nf5 Bxf5 11. Bxf5 O-O 12. Bd3 Qc7 13. g3) 10. f3 Bh5 11. Nxh5 Nxh5 12.
f4 {with the standard ideas.}) 7. dxe5 Nxe5 8. Bf4 Bd6 9. Bxe5 Bxe5 10. Nd2 O-O
11. Nf3 Bc7 12. O-O Bg4 13. Ned4 Ne4 14. Qc2 Re8 15. Rfe1 {should be just
equal but an isolated pawn is an isolated pawn!}) 6... Bg4 {Naturally, Black
has to bring out his light-squared bishop to finish the development with e6
and Be7 or Bd6.} (6... g6 {most likely will transform to lines in Chapter 3.})
7. Qb3 {White tries to exploit the fact that the black pawn on b7 has been
left unprotected. From here I will split the analysis into the remaining
chapters.} e5 $5 {an interesting idea to surprise White but if you're aware of
it, White gets the upper hand in the end. Perhaps the most famous game of this
line is the last round of 2018 US Championship when Samuel Shankland in a
stunning fashion beat Awonder Liang to take the title.} (7... Na5 {for some
reason is not very popular - the arising positions look very much playable to
me.} 8. Qa4+ Bd7 {slightly too passive.} (8... Nc6 {invitation for a draw if
White plays Qb3 next - if never hurts to twice repeat the position and find
out if your opponent really wants it!} 9. Nd2 {for the sake of our database,
we don't want it!} e6 10. Ngf3 Bd6 11. Ne5 O-O 12. Bg3 {[%cal Ga4g4,Gd4e5]
notice how Black can't capture on e5 because the queen from a4 attacks the
bishop on g4!} Qc7 13. Nxg4 Nxg4 14. Qd1 Nf6 15. O-O {[%csl Gd3] with a
classic slight edge for White because of the light-squared bishop and
possibilities to bother the black king at the kingside by the means of Bxd6
and f2-f4. In the particular game Black decided to solve his opening problems
with a radical, yet classical solution.} Bxg3 16. hxg3 e5 17. dxe5 Nxe5 18. Nf3
{0-1 (54) Mueller, K (2545)-Agdestein, S (2545) Germany 1998. Black should be
slightly suffering here, yet somehow he won the game.}) 9. Qc2 e6 10. Nf3 {
the arising position feels like an improved Exchange Slav where the pawn on e3
has been moved to c3.} Qb6 {[%cal Rd7b5]} 11. a4 $1 {a powerful novelty,
unleashed by Fischer some 50 years ago! The weakness of the b3 square is
irrelevant as Black can't exploit it.} Rc8 12. Nbd2 Nc6 13. Qb1 Nh5 14. Be3 $1
{[%csl Rh5] the dark-squared bishop is more important than the knight - by
temporarily moving it to a bad square, it will come to life later. Notice how
useless feels the black knight on h5.} h6 15. Ne5 Nf6 (15... Nxe5 16. dxe5 Bc5
17. a5 $1 {[%csl Rh5][%cal Gg2g4]} Qd8 18. Nf3 $1 g5 19. Qc1 $16 {doesn't look
fun for Black as well.}) 16. h3 Bd6 17. O-O Kf8 $2 18. f4 Be8 19. Bf2 Qc7 20.
Bh4 Ng8 21. f5 $1 $16 {1-0 (39) Fischer,R-Petrosian,T Belgrade 1970. Most
likely, Black can improve the game somewhere along the way but White's
gameplan seems to be quite straightforward.}) (7... Qb6 {A relatively rare
continuation. Black willingly accepts a slightly worse position but is
confident that he can hold it. Whether he really can, it's up to you.} 8. Qxb6
axb6 9. Nd2 (9. Na3 {[%cal Ga3b5,Gb5c7] is very tempting but it only leads to
simplifying the position.} e6 10. Nb5 Kd7 {[%cal Rf6e8,Re8d6]}) 9... e6 10.
Ngf3 {obviously the remaining moves are not forced and the following game is
one of many. Either way, Black is slightly worse because of the doubled pawns.}
Nd7 11. O-O f6 12. Rfe1 Kf7 13. a3 Bh5 14. h3 Bg6 15. Bb5 Be7 16. Re3 Rhe8 17.
Rae1 Nf8 18. c4 $16 {1-0 (43) Yudasin,L (2556)-Bonin,J (2342) New York 2004}) (
7... Qc8 {analysis in Chapter 8}) (7... Qd7 {analysis in Chapter 9}) 8. h3 $5 {
[%cal Gf4h2,Gd4e5,Rf6h5] a very interesting intermezzo! Now in some occasions
White is threatening to play dxe5 and after Nh5 he can hide his bishop with
Bh2!} (8. dxe5 {also looks reasonable and perhaps is the simplest approach
which doesn't promise Black immediate equality.} Nh5 9. Be3 Nxe5 10. Bb5+
Nc6 11. Be2 $5 Bxe2 12. Nxe2 Qd7 13. Nd2 Be7 14. Nf3 O-O 15. Rd1 Rfd8 16. O-O
Nf6 17. Bg5 Ne4 18. Bxe7 Nxe7 19. Rfe1 Qc7 20. Ng3 $14 {1/2-1/2 (35) Yudasin,L
(2507)-Khamrakulov,D (2517) New York 2019}) (8. Qxb7 $5 {I was really
surprised when I discovered that no one's really trying the most obvious move
in this position! So far the practice has seen only 1 game in this line. If White
goes for it, Black achieves equality in the end but I think it would be
interesting to test it in practice!} Rb8 {probably this is the most solid way
to equalize.} (8... exf4 {this order of the moves allows one more extra line
which Black can avoid for the sake of simplicity, not that it's dangerous.} 9.
Bb5) (8... Na5 {Perhaps this is the reason why this line is not so popular? By
playing this Black temporarily wins a piece but now White gets some real
advantage.} 9. Bb5+ Nd7 (9... Bd7 10. Bxd7+ Nxd7 11. Qxd5 exf4 12. b4 Bxb4 13.
cxb4 Rc8 14. Ne2 Nc6 15. Qe4+ Qe7 16. Nbc3 $14) 10. Qxd5 exf4 11. Nf3 $5 $146 {
[%cal Gf3e5] there's always room for improvements!} (11. b4 Bxb4 $1 $146 (11...
Be7 $6 12. bxa5 $6 (12. Be2 $1 $16) 12... O-O 13. Nf3 Qxa5 14. Bc6 Qxd5 15.
Bxd5 Rac8 16. O-O Nb6 17. Bb3 Bxf3 18. gxf3 Rfd8 19. Re1 Bf6 20. a4 a5 21. Ra2
Kf8 22. Rb2 Nc4 23. Bxc4 Rxc4 24. Ra2 Rb8 25. Rd1 Rb6 26. Kf1 Be7 27. Ke2 Rh6
28. Kd3 $14 {0-1 (59) Jarvenpaa,J (2307)-Maki Uuro,M (2347) Finland 2018}) 12.
cxb4 O-O $1 {and Black gets an excellent game as White can't take the knight
on a5.} 13. Nc3 (13. Bxd7 $4 Re8+ $3 14. Kf1 Bxd7 (14... Qc7 {is more
spectacular}) 15. bxa5 Qc8 16. Ne2 f3 17. Qxf3 Bg4 $19) (13. bxa5 $4 Qxa5+ 14.
Kf1 Rac8) 13... Qe7+ 14. Nge2 Bxe2 15. Bxe2 Qxb4 16. O-O Nf6 $11) 11... Bxf3 (
11... Be6 $6 12. Bxd7+ Bxd7 13. Ne5 Be6 14. Qb5+ $1 Ke7 15. Qxa5 Qxa5 16. Nc6+
Kd7 17. Nxa5 $16) 12. gxf3 Rb8 13. Nd2 Be7 14. O-O-O Rb7 15. Rhe1 O-O 16. Ba6
Rb8 17. Rxe7 Qxe7 18. Qxa5 $14) 9. Qxc6+ Bd7 10. Qa6 exf4 11. Nf3 {Probably
White can't afford to waste time to protect the b2 pawn otherwise Black will
get very good compensation.} (11. b4 Qc7 {[%cal Rf8b4,Rc7c1]} 12. Qa3 Bd6 13.
Nf3 O-O 14. O-O Ne4 $44) 11... Rxb2 12. O-O Be7 13. Nbd2 O-O 14. Rfb1 (14. Qxa7
$5) 14... Rxb1+ 15. Rxb1 Qc7 $11) (8. Bxe5 Qe7 $1 {Black immediately gets a
fine game.} 9. Ne2 Nxe5 10. dxe5 Qxe5 11. Qxb7 Rb8 12. Qxa7 Rxb2 13. Qa8+ Kd7
14. Qa7+ Kd8 15. Qa8+ Kc7 16. Qa7+ Kd8 17. Qa8+ Kc7 18. Qa7+ {1/2-1/2 (18)
Stukopin, A (2598)-Postny, E (2586) Rockville 2018}) 8... Na5 $1 {This is the
line of important intermezzos - this one can be easily missed. With this weird
move, Black protects the b7 pawn in the future.} (8... exf4 {the problem of
this most logical move is that because of the b7 pawn weakness it forces Black
to position his queen on an awkward square a move later, asking for a long
castle as a follow-up which not necessarily is good for Black. Very often
White is ready to dismiss his own castling and play Kf1 anyway. Black's score
in this line so far has been disastrous but it doesn't mean it's not playable.}
9. hxg4 {if Black doesn't capture the pawn on g4, then White simply enjoys a
solid positional advantage because of better-positioned pieces and is also
threatening with g4-g5 at some point.} Qe7+ 10. Kf1 $1 Nxg4 {[%cal Rg4f2,Re7e3,
Re3d3] it might seem that Black is doing fine as he has an extra pawn and then
there's the Nxf2 and Qe3+ threat.} (10... O-O-O 11. Nd2 g6 {the pawn on g4
can't be taken because of the Bf5+ trick.} 12. Re1 Qc7 13. g5 Nh5 14. Be2 Ng7
15. Ngf3 Ne6 16. Bb5 Bg7 17. Qa4 Rd6 18. Nb3 b6 19. Nc1 Nb8 20. Nd3 Kb7 21. Nb4
Qd8 22. Ne5 Qc7 23. Qb3 Rhd8 24. Rxh7 {1-0 (43) Shankland,S (2671)-Liang,A 
(2552) Saint Louis 2018}) (10... Ne4 $2 {[%cal Re4f2,Re7e3] seems to be just
bad.} 11. Qc2 O-O-O 12. Nd2 Re8 13. Bxe4 dxe4 14. Re1 f5 15. gxf5 e3 16. fxe3
fxe3 17. Rh3 Qc7 18. Rexe3 Rxe3 19. Rxe3 Bd6 20. Ne2 Rf8 21. Rf3 Re8 22. Ne4
Bf8 23. Qd3 Qf7 24. b3 h6 25. Nf4 {1-0 (25) Demchenko,A (2671)-Yurtseven,M 
(2415) Lisbon 2018}) 11. Nd2 {[%cal Ga1e1]} (11. Qxd5 $2 Nxf2 $1 12. Bb5 Qe4
$17) 11... Qd7 (11... O-O-O $4 12. Bf5+ {is a standard trap of this line.}) 12.
Re1+ Be7 13. Nh3 O-O-O {Black can't afford to waste time protecting the f4
pawn and must quickly bring his king to safety.} (13... Qd6 $5 $146 {this
doesn't feel right but the engines are saying it's possible. Black wants to
keep the f4 pawn for the time being.} 14. Qd1 {[%cal Gd1f3,Gh3f4] there are
many interesting continuations but this one is the simplest - White regains
the pawn with some positional benefits.} (14. Qxb7 Rb8 15. Qa6 O-O 16. b4 Nf6 {
is anything but clear}) 14... h5 15. Qf3 g6 16. Nxf4 O-O-O 17. g3 Bg5 18. Kg2
Bxf4 19. Qxf4 Qxf4 20. gxf4 $14 {[%cal Gd2f3,Gf3e5,Gf3g5]}) 14. Nf3 (14. Nxf4
Bg5 {[%cal Rg5d2] might be unpleasant}) 14... g6 15. Nxf4 $14 {[%csl Rd5][%cal
Gd3b5,Gf4d3] White has an advantage as the d5 pawn is a long-term weakness and
White build up some pressure with ideas like Bd3-b5 and Nf4-d3-c5 or e5. The
king most likely will find shelter after g2-g3 and Kg2 at some point.}) (8...
Be6 $146 {simply drops a pawn but White needs to be accurate.} 9. Bxe5 (9. dxe5
Nh5 10. Bh2 $6 Qg5 $1 $13) 9... Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7 11. Nf3 Nc5 12. Qc2 $14) 9.
Qc2 exf4 {now there will be several forced moves and the position will clarify
a little.} (9... Bd1 $5 {a spectacular move but nothing more - White simply
gets the upper hand.} 10. Qxd1 exf4 11. Nf3 Bd6 12. Nbd2 O-O 13. O-O Re8 14. b4
Nc6 15. Qb3 Rc8 16. Rfe1 Rc7 17. Rxe8+ Qxe8 18. a3 Re7 19. Rd1 Bc7 20. Qc2 g6
21. Nb3 Ne4 22. c4 dxc4 23. Bxc4 Nd6 24. Bf1 {1-0 (41) Vaibhav,S (2597)-Ravi,T
(2455) Majitar 2019}) 10. hxg4 Nxg4 11. Qe2+ {[%cal Ge2e8,Ge2g4]} Qe7 12. Nh3 {
White is regaining the sacrificed pawn by force so Black tries to be creative.}
f3 {Since the extra pawn is falling by force, Black tries to sell his pawn by
ruining White's pawn structure.} 13. Qxe7+ (13. gxf3 {a recent game showed
that also this move is pretty much playable.} Qxe2+ 14. Kxe2 Nf6 15. Nd2 Bd6
16. f4 Nh5 $6 {a difficult to explain move.} (16... O-O $146 17. Nf3 Nc4 $11)
17. Kf3 g6 18. f5 O-O-O 19. Nf1 Nc6 20. Ne3 Ne7 21. Ng5 Rdf8 22. Rxh5 $1 gxh5
23. f6 Ng6 24. Nxd5 h6 25. Ne4 Rd8 26. Rh1 h4 27. Bc4 Bb8 28. Ne3 Rdf8 29. Nf5
$16 {1-0 (37) Demchenko,A (2661)-Postny,E (2612) Fagernes 2019}) 13... Bxe7 14.
g3 $5 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gd2f3] the key move - White keeps his pawn structure
healthy as the f3 pawn is going nowhere.} Nc4 {what else? Black has to justify
his knight's placement on a5 somehow!} (14... O-O $6 {this brave move brings
only trouble for Black.} 15. Nf4 {[%cal Gf4d5,Gd3h7]} Rfe8 16. Kf1 g6 (16...
Nf6 $2 {Seemingly Black is alright as he defends both of his d5 and h7 pawns
but now comes an amazing refutation!} 17. Nxd5 $3 Nxd5 18. Bxh7+ Kf8 19. Be4 {
[%cal Gh1h8]} Bg5 (19... Nf6 20. Rh8+ Ng8 21. Bh7 {is essentially the same})
20. Bxd5 Bc1 21. a4 Bxb2 22. Ra2 Bc1 23. Bxf3 $16 {1-0 (41) Burg,T (2525)-Van
De Velde,H (2124) Leiden 2018}) 17. Nxd5 Bg5 18. Nf4 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gd2f3] with
a clear advantage for White}) 15. Bxc4 dxc4 16. Nd2 Rc8 17. Nxf3 {[%csl Rc4]
[%cal Ga2a4,Ge1g1,Gf3d2] the dust has settled, White seems to be slightly
better because of the protected passed pawn on d4, plus Black might experience
some problems because of the vulnerable c4 pawn.} h6 (17... Kd7 18. Ne5+ $6 (
18. O-O) 18... Nxe5 19. dxe5 Rc5 20. O-O-O+ Kc6 21. f4 Rd5 22. Nf2 Rxd1+ 23.
Kxd1 h6 24. Ke2 Rd8 $11 {1/2-1/2 (60) Demchenko,A (2670)-Postny,E (2576)
Teplice 2018}) 18. a4 Kd7 19. O-O g5 20. Rfe1 b6 21. Kg2 f6 22. Nd2 $14 {
[%cal Ge1e2,Ga1e1] ½-½ (22) Bacrot,E (2714)-Istratescu,A (2589) Brest 2018.}
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Chapter 8 - 5...Nf6, 7...Qc8"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B13"]
[Annotator "GM Arturs Neiksans"]
[PlyCount "39"]
[SourceVersionDate "2018.11.06"]

1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 7. Qb3 Qc8 {
One of the main moves which feels like a more careful approach - the other
popular continuation here is 7...Qd7 which comes together with Bd6 and a
potential pawn sacrifice on b7.} (7... Na5 {This is an old fashioned move -
Bobby Fischer beat Tigran Petrosian in this line exactly 50 years ago! There
have been some attempts to revive this line.} 8. Qa4+ {forcing the bishop to
go to a much more passive square.} Bd7 9. Qc2 e6 {this leads to the famous
game. The choice, however, feels slightly passive.} (9... Nh5 $5 {[%cal Gh2b8]
is the modern approach, as Black fights for control of the h2-b8 diagonal.} 10.
Be3 Qc7 {[%cal Rh5f4] Black intends to play Nf4 real soon.} (10... g6 11. Nf3
Bg7 12. Nbd2 O-O 13. O-O {[%cal Rd8c7,Rh5f4,Gf1e1,Gd3f1] here the late Qc7 and
Nh5-f4 can be met with Rfe1 and Bd3-f1 with ideas to play Nf3-e5.} f5 {trying
to justify the knight's placement on h5, but this weakens the e5 square
forever.} 14. Nb3 Nc4 15. Qe2 Nxe3 16. Qxe3 b6 17. Rfe1 e6 18. Ne5 Ba4 19. Nd2
Qe7 20. Ndf3 $14 {1/2-1/2 (24) Novikov,M (2510)-Gusev,A (2411) Bogoroditsk 2011
}) 11. Nf3 Nc6 (11... Nf4 $6 {would be a too hasty decision.} 12. Bxf4 Qxf4 13.
Ne5 {[%csl Rd7]}) 12. O-O Nf4 13. Bxf4 Qxf4 14. Re1 e6 15. Nbd2 Bd6 16. Nb3 {
[%cal Gb3c5,Ge1e3,Ga1e1] White feels a little better because of the control of
the central squares, but it's not much.}) (9... a6 {[%cal Rd7b5] with the same
idea to exchange the light-squared bishops but here it would double the
b-pawns. White has a pleasant choice.} 10. Nd2 (10. a4 $5 Bg4 {[%cal Rg4h5,
Rh5g6] Black does trade the bishops after all, but it costs him quite a few
tempos. Thus White should have at least an edge.} 11. Nd2 Bh5 12. Ngf3 Bg6 13.
Ne5 e6 14. O-O Bd6 15. Rfe1 O-O 16. Nxg6 hxg6 17. Be5 Bxe5 18. dxe5 Nd7 19. b4
Nc6 20. Nf3 Rc8 21. Qe2 Ne7 22. Rac1 Nf5 23. a5 Qe7 24. g3 Rc7 25. Kg2 Rfc8 26.
Qd2 Nb8 27. h4 $14 {0-1 (42) Campora,D (2540)-Tukmakov,V (2590) Biel 1988})
10... e6 11. Ngf3 Bb5 12. Bxb5+ axb5 {Now Black has got what he wanted but
White's game is very easy and Black is struggling to find a game plan or some
targets.} 13. a3 Be7 14. O-O O-O 15. Rae1 Nc4 16. Ne5 Ra6 17. Nd3 Rc6 18. Qd1
Rb6 19. Nf3 Ne4 20. Nfe5 Bf6 21. f3 Ned6 22. Ng4 Bh4 23. g3 Bg5 24. Bxd6 Nxd6
25. h4 Be7 26. h5 {Essentially White has a free attack at the kingside while
Black has to sit and wait. 1-0 (82) Aronian, L (2765)-Karjakin, S (2753) Kolkata
2018}) 10. Nf3 {feels like an improved Exchange Slav.} Qb6 {[%cal Rd7b5] Black
is threatening to exchange the light-squared bishops} 11. a4 $1 Rc8 (11... Qb3
12. Qe2) 12. Nbd2 Nc6 13. Qb1 Nh5 14. Be3 h6 15. Ne5 Nf6 16. h3 Bd6 17. O-O Kf8
$2 18. f4 Be8 19. Bf2 Qc7 20. Bh4 Ng8 21. f5 $16 {1-0 (39) Fischer,R-Petrosian,
T Belgrade 1970}) 8. Nd2 {[%cal Rg4h5,Rh5g6,Gg1f3] Preparing to play Ngf3.
Because of the need to protect the b7 pawn the f5 square is out of bounds so
in order to trade the light-squared bishop Black is going to play Bh5-g6 at
some moment. The question is - which is the right moment? There are quite
subtle nuances.} e6 (8... Bh5 9. Ngf3 Bg6 {this is probably the earliest
attempt and this gives White an interesting opportunity.} 10. Bb5 $5 {[%cal
Gf3e5,Gb3a4] with a very simple threat of Nf3-e5 and Qa4. This idea might be
possible in various order of the moves, should Black rush with Bh5-g6.} a6 11.
Bxc6+ {now Black is at crossroads - it pretty much doesn't matter with what he
will take as White's approach will be the same, to push c3-c4.} bxc6 (11...
Qxc6 12. a4 $1 {it's quite important to take away the b5 square before pushing
c3-c4 to avoid a queen trade.} e6 13. Ne5 Qc8 14. O-O Be7 15. Rac1 O-O 16. c4
$14 {[%csl Rb6,Rb7] and things look really unpleasant for Black, mostly
because of the weak b6 square and the pawn on b7 feels quite vulnerable.}) 12.
Qa4 Nd7 13. O-O e6 14. c4 Nb6 (14... Bd3 $2 15. Rfc1 Qb7 (15... Nb6 $4 16. Qb3
{[%cal Gb3b6,Gb3d3] going for the c4 pawn doesn't work for Black as he simply
drops a piece}) 16. cxd5 cxd5 17. Rc7 Qb5 18. Qxb5 Bxb5 19. a4 Be2 20. Re1 Bxf3
21. Nxf3 $16) 15. Qa5 Nxc4 16. Nxc4 dxc4 17. Ne5 Qb7 18. Nxc4 {[%csl Rc6] and
because of the weakness on c6 Black is suffering.} Bb4 19. Qb6 Qxb6 20. Nxb6
Rd8 21. Rfd1 Bd6 22. Bxd6 Rxd6 23. Rac1 Ke7 24. Nc4 Rd5 25. Ne5 f6 26. Nxg6+
hxg6 27. Rxc6 $14 {1-0 (50) Pospisil,L (2489)-Deskin,G (2160) ICCF email 2016})
9. Ngf3 Be7 (9... Bh5 {one more attempt to land the bishop on g6 early.} 10.
O-O Bg6 (10... Be7 11. Rae1 {will transpose to the main line}) 11. Bb5 $5 {
also here it should work!} a6 (11... Be7 {if Black doesn't play a7-a6, he has
to give up his light-squared bishop for a knight.} 12. Ne5 O-O 13. Nxg6 hxg6
14. Bd3 {[%cal Gd2f3,Gg2g3,Gg1g2,Gh2h4,Gh4h5] and we're back to the
traditional plan - Nf3, g2-g3, Kg1-g2, h2-h4, Rf1-h1 and prepare h4-h5.}) 12.
Bxc6+ bxc6 (12... Qxc6 13. a4 Bd6 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. c4 O-O 16. c5 Qc7 17. Rfc1
{White feels better.}) 13. Qa4 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gf3e5]} (13. c4 Nh5 14. Be5 f6
15. cxd5 exd5 (15... fxe5 $5) 16. Rfe1 Kf7 17. Rac1 Kg8 18. Bg3 Nxg3 19. hxg3
Qd7 20. Qa4 Be8 21. Qc2 Bd6 22. Nb3 a5 23. Nc5 Bxc5 24. Qxc5 Kf7 25. Re3 a4 26.
Rce1 Ra7 27. Ra3 Qb7 28. b3 Rf8 29. bxa4 Kg8 30. Rae3 Ra8 31. Rb3 Qa7 32. Qxa7
Rxa7 33. Rb4 Bd7 34. Nd2 c5 35. dxc5 Bxa4 36. Nf3 Bc2 37. Nd4 Rxa2 38. Rb7 Ba4
39. Ree7 Ra1+ 40. Kh2 {1-0 (40) Stojanovski,D (2429)-Camber,I (1948) Rijeka
2008}) 13... Nh5 (13... Nd7 14. c4 {transforms to a line, covered earlier.})
14. Be3 Bd6 15. Ne5 O-O 16. Qxc6 (16. c4 $5) 16... Bxe5 17. Qxc8 Bxh2+ 18. Kxh2
Rfxc8 19. Nb3 Rab8 20. Bc1 Nf6 21. Nc5 $14 {[%cal Gf2f3,Gb2b4,Ga2a4]}) (9...
Bxf3 10. Nxf3 $14 {[%cal Gb3c2,Gc2e2,Gf3e5,Ge1g1] gives White immediately a
solid advantage and chances to build an attack at the kingside.}) 10. O-O Bh5 {
probably this is the best moment when Black could reroute the bishop to g6,
and this is why it's quite popular at the top level.} (10... O-O 11. Qc2 $1 {
and now it's slightly too late for Black to reroute the bishop on g6 as White
will keep his light-squared bishop!} Bh5 (11... Bf5 {engines think that this
is a playable move and they might be right. But from a human's perspective
Black has ruined his pawn structure and almost any endgame should be in
White's favour.} 12. Bxf5 exf5 13. Rfe1) 12. Ne5 a6 {obviously, Black can't
take on e5 as after dxe5 he loses a pawn on h7.} 13. Rae1 Bg6 {this is not
mandatory and it's entirely possible that Black can postpone this decision and
start with b7-b5 and focus at the queenside first, but he will have to do this
sooner or later.} (13... b5 14. Re3 {[%cal Ge3h3]}) 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. Nf3 {
with a very simple plan at the kingside.} b5 16. a3 Ra7 17. Qe2 Re8 18. h4 Bd8
19. g3 Ne7 20. Kg2 Nf5 21. Rh1 Bc7 22. Ne5 Bb8 23. g4 Nd6 24. h5 {With a
winning attack. Seemingly Black made normal looking moves - can you clearly
pinpoint his mistake? 1-0 (36) Berkes,F (2661)-McShane,L (2647) Heraklio 2017})
11. Rae1 {The bishop trade is going to happen so White concentrates all his
forces at the kingside.} (11. Ne5 Nxe5 $1 (11... O-O 12. Qc2 {would transform
to a favourable line where Black most likely will have to give up his
light-squared bishop for a knight.}) 12. Bxe5 O-O 13. c4 $5 dxc4 14. Nxc4 Bg6
15. Bxg6 hxg6 16. Rac1 Qd7 17. Na5 b6 18. Rc7 Qe8 19. Nc6 Bd8 20. Nxd8 Qxd8 21.
Qa4 Nd5 22. Rxa7 Rxa7 23. Qxa7 Qa8 24. Qxa8 Rxa8 25. a3 Rc8 26. h4 f6 27. Bg3
Rc2 $44 {1/2-1/2 (27) Sedlak,N (2559)-Gledura,B (2414) Hungary 2015}) (11. Rfe1
Bg6 12. Bb5 {specifically here this doesn't look so great as Black can both
castle and avoid playing early a7-a6.} O-O {Taking on c6 is not so appealing
anymore if Black doesn't play a6 and weaken his b6 square.} 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14.
Bxe5 a6 15. Be2 Nd7 $11) 11... Bg6 {For Black it's better to trade the bishop
before castling} (11... O-O {Black can also postpone the bishop's rerouting to
g6 but practice proves that this is a dangerous idea - White's attack becomes
quite obvious.} 12. Qc2 {Still intending to play Nf3-e5, if allowed,
transposing to some of the covered lines.} (12. g3 $5 $146 {[%cal Gg1g2,Gh2h4]
for the sake of simplicity White can stick to his original plan and continue
with Kg1-g2, h2-h4 and at some point - Ne5. Black will have to play Bg6 at
some point anyway, so the position will transpose to one of the main lines.})
12... Bg6 13. Bxg6 hxg6 14. Qd3 {[%cal Rb7b5,Gd3h3,Gf3g5] keeping an eye on
b7-b5 and preparing to reroute the queen to h3.} a6 15. Ng5 Nh5 16. Qh3 {
[%cal Gg2g4]} Re8 {[%cal Re6e5]} (16... Bxg5 17. Bxg5 Re8 18. f4 $146 {[%cal
Gg2g4]} (18. Qh4 e5 19. dxe5 Nxe5 20. h3 Qc6 21. Qd4 Nd7 22. Be7 Nhf6 23. Re3
Nf8 24. Bxf6 gxf6 25. Rfe1 Rxe3 26. Rxe3 Kg7 27. Nf1 Ne6 28. Qd2 Nc5 29. Ng3
Ne4 30. Qd4 Re8 31. Ne2 Ng5 32. Nf4 Re4 33. Rxe4 dxe4 34. Nd5 Qe6 35. c4 Qf5
36. Qb6 Nxh3+ 37. gxh3 {1-0 (37) Gabuzyan,H (2613)-Sorokin,A (2531) Chicago
2019})) 17. Ndf3 b5 18. Bc1 Bxg5 19. Bxg5 f6 20. g4 $1 $146 (20. Be3 $6 e5 21.
g4 exd4 22. Nxd4 Ne5 23. f3 Nd3 24. Qh4 Nhf4 25. Bxf4 Nxe1 26. Rxe1 g5 27.
Rxe8+ Qxe8 28. Bxg5 fxg5 29. Qxg5 $11 {1-0 (116) Melkumyan,H (2660)-Belenkaya,
D (2357) Caleta 2019}) 20... e5 21. Qg2 fxg5 22. gxh5 $16) 12. Bxg6 hxg6 {
Black is very solid but actually because of the doubled pawns, White can think
about a future attack at the kingside, linked with h2-h4-h5.} 13. g3 $5 {
[%cal Gh2h4,Gg1g2] First played by Jan Krzysztof Duda last year - I like this
move the most. White is going to play g2-g3 anyway as it fits the concept so
why not play it immediately? The idea remains the same - play h2-h4, Kg2, Rh1
and aim for a kingside attack once Black will short castle.} (13. h4 $5 {
[%cal Gg2g3,Gg1g2,Gf1h1] was first played by Vladimir Kramnik in his World Cup
match against Vasyl Ivanchuk back in 2017. The idea is not to waste time and
prepare for a kingside attack with the following g2-g3, Kg2 and Rh1, should
Black make a short castle.} a6 14. c4 (14. a4 Nh5 15. Bh2 Nf6 {Instead of the
repetition, it's difficult to come up here with a move for White! I am pretty
sure that Carlsen went here deliberately as draw secured him a win in the
mini-match.} 16. Bf4 Nh5 17. Bh2 Nf6 18. Bf4 {½-½ (18) Carlsen,M (2863)-So,W 
(2770) Lindores Abbey 2020}) 14... a5 15. a3 a4 16. Qd3 O-O 17. c5 b6 18. cxb6
Qb7 19. Bc7 Nd7 {0-1 (71) Kramnik,V (2803)-Ivanchuk,V (2728) Tbilisi 2017})
13... O-O {the most logical move although maybe Black can postpone castling
for some time and focus on queenside activities first.} (13... a6 14. h4 b5 15.
Kg2 (15. a3 Kf8 16. Kg2 Nh5 17. Bg5 Bd6 18. Ne5 Qc7 $2 19. Ndf3 (19. Nxg6+ $1
fxg6 20. Rxe6) 19... Re8 20. Qd1 Nf6 21. Nxc6 Qxc6 22. Bxf6 gxf6 23. Re2 a5 24.
Qd3 Qc4 25. Ne1 Rb8 26. Rc2 Kg7 27. Rh1 Rbc8 28. Qe3 Qb3 29. Qf3 Qa4 30. h5
Rxh5 31. Rxh5 gxh5 32. Qxh5 b4 33. axb4 axb4 34. Qe2 bxc3 35. bxc3 Qc4 {
1/2-1/2 (35) Kopinits,A (2209)-Cvitan,E (2289) Austria 2020}) 15... Qb7 16. Rh1
{[%cal Gf3e5] and the question is - for how long can the black king remain in
the centre? Objectively the position remains equal.}) (13... Nh5 14. Be3 ({
the immediate} 14. Bg5 {can run into some hostilities after} f6 15. Be3 g5 $13)
14... O-O 15. Kg2 Nf6 16. Bg5 a6 17. h4) 14. Kg2 $146 {Technically a novelty,
but the idea remains the same.} (14. Ne5 {Duda played this in the game. I can
only assume he was somewhat concerned about the potential Nf6-h5 idea and wasn't
too fond of the option to trade the dark-squared bishops. Thus he removed the
idea for good and forced the other black knight to retreat to d7. However,
here White's attack feels slightly unprepared and gives Black plenty of
chances to organize a counter-attack at the queenside.} Nxe5 15. dxe5 Nd7 16.
h4 Nc5 17. Qc2 Qc6 18. Re3 Qa6 19. Qb1 Rac8 20. Kg2 b5 21. Bg5 Qb7 22. Bxe7
Qxe7 23. Rh1 a5 24. Qd1 b4 25. Qg4 bxc3 26. bxc3 Rb8 27. h5 g5 28. h6 g6 29.
Nf3 Ne4 $11 {0-1 (50) Duda,J (2738)-Van Foreest,J (2612) Wijk aan Zee 2019})
14... a6 15. h4 b5 16. Ne5 {from here the following lines are not forced and
they merely illustrate the idea how the game might continue.} Qb7 {[%cal Rb7g2]
} 17. Rh1 {[%cal Gb3d1,Gf4g5,Gh4h5]} Nh5 (17... Nxe5 18. dxe5 {I think it's
important to aim for the position where White can capture on e5 with a pawn,
otherwise pushing h4-h5 doesn't look too real.} Nh5 19. Bg5 d4+ 20. Ne4 dxc3
21. Qxc3 {[%cal Gc3f3,Gg3g4]}) (17... a5 18. Bg5 a4 (18... b4 19. Qc2 Rfc8 20.
Qd3 {[%cal Gg5f6,Gh4h5]}) 19. Qc2 b4 (19... a3 20. Bxf6 Bxf6 21. Ng4 Rfc8 22.
Nf3 axb2 23. h5 Ne7 24. hxg6 Nxg6 25. Rxe6 $1 $40) 20. Bxf6 gxf6 (20... Bxf6
21. Ng4 {[%cal Gh4h5]}) 21. Nxg6 fxg6 22. Qxg6+ Kh8 23. Nf3 $40 {[%cal Gf3g5,
Ge1e6]}) 18. Bg5 Rae8 (18... f6 $4 19. Nxg6 fxg5 20. Rxe6 {and Black's
position falls apart.}) 19. Qc2 b4 20. Ndf3 {[%cal Gc2d2,Gg3g4] the black
knight can't stay on h5 forever as it will be pushed out, thus h4-h5 should
happen in a near future. I like White's chances.} *

