1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nc6 5. c3 Nf6 6. Bf4 Bg4 7. Qb3 Qd7 {
[%cal Re7e6,Rf8d6] the most ambitious move - Black is not afraid of any early
Nf3-e5 ideas and wants to trade the dark-squared bishops with Bd6, even if it
costs him a pawn on b7.} 8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 {White's plan doesn't change,
whether the black queen is on c8 or d7 - focus on the game at the kingside as
this is where the black king will be.} Bd6 {I think the best approach for
Black is to keep his light-squared bishop.} (9... Bxf3 {It is my understanding
that early giving up the light-squared bishop on f3 makes White's life a
little easier, with some extra options. The bishop on d3 does a wonderful job
attacking the kingside and also keeping an eye on the queenside.} 10. Nxf3 Bd6
11. Bg3 $1 {[%csl Ge5] If Black has traded his light-squared bishop, White
doesn't have to give up the control of the e5 square.} (11. Bxd6 {is the other
reasonable alternative which will feel quite similar to the main lines.} Qxd6
12. O-O O-O (12... Rb8 13. a4 (13. Rae1 O-O) 13... O-O 14. Rfe1 Nd7 15. a5 h6
16. Qa3 Qxa3 17. Rxa3 Rfc8 {1-0 (52) Jumabayev,R (2612)-Saric,I (2669) Riadh
2017}) 13. Rae1 {will transform into one of the main lines of this chapter.} (13.
Qxb7 Rab8 14. Qa6 {[%cal Gf3e5,Gd3b5]} Rb6 15. Qa3 Qxa3 16. bxa3 Rc8 17. Rab1
Na5 $44)) 11... O-O 12. O-O Bxg3 13. hxg3 Qc7 14. Rfe1 Rab8 (14... Nd7 $5 $146
15. Qc2 h6 16. Qd2 a6 17. g4 $14 {[%cal Gg4g5,Gg2g3,Gg1g2] I have a feeling
that Black will have to push e6-e5 and try to hold a slightly worse position,
otherwise White's attack looks quite dangerous.}) 15. Qc2 b5 16. a3 a5 17. Ne5
{1/2-1/2 (17) Smirin,I (2615)-Khalifman,A (2645) Elenite 1994} (17. Qe2 $5 b4
18. cxb4 axb4 19. a4 $14)) 10. Bxd6 ({here} 10. Bg3 {doesn't look so
interesting as Black still has the light-squared bishop which can be rerouted
to h5.} Bh5 {[%cal Rh5g6]}) (10. Ne5 {is tempting but gives nothing. Doesn't
mean it's unplayable!} Qc7 11. Nxg4 Bxf4 12. Nxf6+ gxf6 13. Nf3 $11) 10... Qxd6
11. O-O O-O {I believe all of this is more or less forced and this is where
White has to make a choice.} (11... Bh5 $6 12. Qxb7 {if Black wants to make
everything out of the opening, he has to make sure that White can't really
take the pawn on b7. Here, it seems, it's simply a free pawn.} Rb8 13. Qa6 {
[%cal Gd3b5]} Rb6 14. Qa4 $16 {and Black is not in time to grab back the pawn
on b2.}) 12. Rae1 {[%cal Gf3e5,Gf2f4,Ge1e3] This is the move that I like the
most - White doesn't hide his plan to play at the kingside with the
traditional ideas of Nf3-e5, Re3-h3 and probably f2-f4. Plus, it's the same
rook manoeuvre as in Chapter 8. Let us stop here for a moment as Black is at
the crossroads. As far as I can see, these are his options:  1) Continue with
the traditional plan and reroute the bishop on g6. However, with the short
castle already done, Black has to understand that there might be a quick and
annoying attack at the h-file.  2) Play Nd7 to stop White from playing Nf3-e5
and f2-f4. This allows White almost by force to exchange Black's light-squared
bishop and create some targets at the kingside.  3) Black can trade on f3
right away and focus at the queenside. By doing so he wouldn't have to worry
about a quick attack at the h-file (had the bishop been rerouted to g6 and
traded there) but this gives White quite a lot of freedom.  4) Ignore White's
ideas, keep the bishop on g4 as long as it takes and focus on his own ideas at
the queenside.  Not surprisingly, the last two ideas at the moment are the
most popular choices.} (12. Rfe1 {might be a more modest alternative, keeping
the other rook at the queenside for the time being, as a2-a4 might be an
option at some point.} Rab8 (12... Nd7 13. Qc2 {A nice trick to force Black to
exchange his light-squared bishop.} h6 14. h3 Bxf3 (14... Bh5 $6 15. g4) 15.
Nxf3 $14) 13. Ne5 Bh5 14. a4 a6 15. a5 {however, by doing this White should
understand that he won't have the time to play on both kingside and
queenside, thus an attack against the king looks unlikely to happen.}) 12...
Rab8 {Black completely ignores what's happening at the kingside and focuses
instead on making b7-b5-b4 to happen as quickly as possible. This also gives
him some room for improvisation, for example, at the right time to reroute the
bishop to g6.} (12... Nd7 13. Qc2 h6 {the most played move in the position,
however, I do think that the lesser-played alternative is better.} (13... g6 $1
{[%cal Rg4f5]} 14. Re3 {It's quite difficult to prove that White has here
anything at all. I suggest the text move, preparing against Bf5 by either
doubling the rooks at the e-file, or transfer one of them to h3, and would
avoid playing h2-h3, if possible.} Bf5 15. Bxf5 gxf5 (15... exf5 16. Rfe1) 16.
Ng5 {[%cal Ge3h3,Ge3g3]}) 14. h3 Bxf3 (14... Bh5 $6 15. g4) 15. Nxf3 {[%cal
Gg2g3,Gh3h4,Gg1g2,Gc2d2] with a lot of manoeuvring at the kingside. Black will
continue with his traditional b7-b5-b4 plan.}) (12... Bxf3 {One of the most
popular continuations but this gives White quite a lot of freedom to improvise
at the kingside.} 13. Nxf3 Qc7 14. Qc2 {[%cal Gf3e5] the queen has nothing to
do at the queenside anymore and should be rerouted closer to the kingside.
White is threatening to play Ne5 and Black should do something about it,
otherwise, the follow-up after that will be f2-f4.} g6 (14... Rac8 {[%cal Rc6b4]
} 15. Qe2 a6 16. g3 b5 17. a3 Rfe8 18. Kg2 Rb8 19. h4 h6 20. Rh1 Nd7 21. Bb1 a5
22. Qd3 Nf8 23. b4 Rec8 24. Re3 Rb7 25. Rhe1 Qb6 26. Nd2 a4 27. Nf3 Rbc7 28.
Qd2 Qb8 29. h5 Rb7 30. Nh2 Qd6 31. Ng4 $14 {0-1 (51) Kovalev,V (2636)
-Riazantsev,A (2666) Sochi 2017}) (14... h6 15. g3 {[%cal Gg1g2,Gc2d2,Gh2h4]
and so on.}) 15. Qd2 Kg7 16. Ne5 $5 {a rare move in this particular position,
a long time ago played by then young Hikaru Nakamura - I don't think
everything is clear here as it looks interesting.} (16. Re3 Rab8 17. a4 a6 18.
Rfe1 Qf4 19. Qd1 b5 20. axb5 axb5 21. b4 Rfc8 22. h3 Qc7 23. Nd2 Ne7 24. Bc2
Nf5 25. Bxf5 gxf5 26. Nb3 Ne4 27. Nc5 $11 {0-1 (61) Ter Sahakyan,S (2563)
-Swapnil,S (2533) chess.com INT 2018}) 16... Nxe5 17. dxe5 Nd7 18. Qf4 {
[%cal Ge1e3,Gh2h4]} Kg8 19. h4 $5 $146 (19. Qg5 Qd8 20. Qh6 {[%cal Ge1e3,Ge3h3]
1/2-1/2 (20) Nakamura,H (2452)-Doettling,F (2518) Boston 2001}) 19... f6 20. h5
Nxe5 21. hxg6 hxg6 22. Bxg6 Kg7 23. Qg3 $14) (12... Bh5 13. Ne5 Qc7 14. f4 {
[%cal Ge1e3,Ge3h3]} Bg6 15. Bxg6 $1 {[%csl Ge5] I think it's important to keep
the knight on e5 - the bishop has done its job and thus it's alright to trade
it.} hxg6 16. Re3 {[%cal Ge3h3,Gb3d1,Gd1e1,Ge1h4] it can be quite problematic
to come up with a proper defense against the simple White's plan.} Qb6 {
perhaps already a necessity.} (16... Ne7 17. Rh3 Nf5 18. g4 Nd6 19. Qd1 Nfe4
20. Nxe4 Nxe4 21. Qe1 Qe7 22. g5 {[%cal Ge1h4] is a sample line of how quickly
can Black get checkmated.}) 17. Qxb6 axb6 18. a3 {with a long and manoeuvring
game. Notice that Black pawns are quite static thus I imagine that only White
can make a progress by carefully advancing the pawns at the kingside. Once the
black knight will land on c4, it should be ignored and the white knight on d3
keeps everything protected.}) (12... Ne7 $5 {[%cal Rg4f5] In the Chessable
course "Lifetime Repertoires: Caro Kann" the Dutch GM Erwin L'Ami gives the
following continuation for Black as a recommendation - Black is threatening
with the immediate Bg4-f5 and not spoiling his pawn structure. It seems that
there's nothing that White can do about it but treat it this way - Black loses
a lot of tempos in the process and White gains a considerable space advantage
at the kingside. If Black will play it out perfectly, probably he will manage
to equalize in the end, however, it is White who is constantly pushing Black
and not the other way around.} 13. Ne5 Bf5 14. Bxf5 Nxf5 15. g4 {it's time to
grab some additional space advantage!} (15. Qxb7 {is not really impressive
here as after} Rab8 16. Qxa7 Rxb2 17. Nb3 Qe7 $1 {[%cal Rf6e4] Black has plenty of compensation for the sacrificed pawn. For example,} 18. Qa5 Ne4 19.
c4 Qb7 {[%cal Rf8a8]} 20. Nd3 (20. Qa3 Rc2 21. Rc1 Re2) 20... Rc2 21. cxd5 Ra8
22. Qb4 Qxd5 23. Nf4 Qc6 24. Rc1 h6 $11) 15... Ne7 (15... Nh4 {is also
possible but most likely it will be rerouted to g6 and after that - to e7
anyway.} 16. f4 {[%csl Rh4][%cal Gb3d1,Ge1e3,Gd1e2]}) 16. Qb5 $146 {[%cal
Gb5d3,Gd3e2] My suggested improvement, which is also similar to what Kotronias
did in the only game in this line - the queen is immediately transferred to
either d3 or e2, while f2-f4 can wait for the moment. Black can't play b7-b5
just yet.} (16. f4 b5 $1 $146 {Llami's suggested continuation which looks
quite strong as Black is not wasting time for the preparation moves a6 and Rb8.
} (16... Rab8 17. Qb5 a6 18. Qd3 b5 19. f5 (19. a3 a5 20. f5 exf5 21. gxf5 b4
22. cxb4 axb4 23. a4 Ra8 24. Re2 Rxa4 25. Rg2 Ra7 26. Qg3 g6 27. fxg6 fxg6 28.
Rgf2 Raa8 29. Qg5 Ne4 30. Nxe4 dxe4 31. Nf7 Qe6 32. Nh6+ Kg7 33. Rf7+ Rxf7 34.
Rxf7+ Qxf7 35. Nxf7 Kxf7 36. Qf4+ {1-0 (65) Kotronias,V (2505)-Olsen,F (2354)
Aarhus 2018}) 19... exf5 20. gxf5 b4 21. Re2 $36 {[%cal Ge2g2]}) 17. g5 (17. f5
{unfortunately doesn't give the desired results} exf5 18. gxf5 Rab8 19. Re2 b4
20. Rg2 Nc6 $1 21. Nxc6 Qxc6 22. cxb4 Qb6 23. Qe3 Rfe8 $11) 17... Ne8 {however,
starting from here the game is not forced. Probably the pawn on b5 is
untouchable due to the typical Rb8-Rxb2 but White has a potential to increase
the pressure at the kingside where he enjoys a solid space advantage.} (17...
Nh5 $5 18. Qxb5 Ng6 19. Qe2 (19. f5 Ngf4 20. Qd7 Qb6 $13) 19... Ngxf4 (19...
Nhxf4 $6 20. Qe3 Nh5 21. Nxg6 hxg6 22. Nf3 $16 {[%csl Rh5]}) 20. Qe3 f6 21.
gxf6 gxf6 22. Nd3 Nxd3 23. Qxd3 Kh8 24. Kh1 Rab8 25. Nb3 e5 26. Qh3 Nf4 27. Qf5
Ng6 $11) 18. Rf3 Nf5 19. Qd1 Qe7 20. Qe2 (20. Rh3 f6 21. Qh5 g6 {there is no
mate.}) 20... b4 21. Nb3 bxc3 22. bxc3 Ned6 23. Nc5 Nb7 24. Nxb7 Qxb7 25. Rh3
f6 26. gxf6 Rxf6 27. Kh1 $11) 16... a6 (16... Qc7 $5 {this might be a smart
approach to wait for White to play f2-f4 first so that Black can gain control
of the e4 square.} 17. Qe2 {there's no need to rush with the f-pawn first. At
times playing out this variation can feel like playing cat and mouse.} (17. f4
Nc8 18. g5 Nd6 19. Qe2 Nfe4 20. Nxe4 Nxe4 $11) 17... Nc8 18. g5 Nd7 19. f4 Nd6
20. Rf3 g6 (20... Nxe5 21. fxe5 Nf5 22. Nf1 {[%cal Gf1e3,Ge3g4]}) 21. Rh3 Rae8
22. Kh1 {and all eyes are what's happening at the kingside. Black's
counterplay at the queenside is both late and irrelevant at the moment. Black
still looks too solid to break through immediately.}) 17. Qd3 (17. Qe2 b5 18.
Nd3 {[%cal Gd3b4,Gd3c5,Gd3e5,Gd3f4] also looks fairly interesting, with the
knight on d3 controlling many critical squares around, including b4 and c5, so
that White can focus on the kingside.}) 17... b5 {if Black follows the
traditional approach and organizes a counter-attack at the queenside, White
should be a little faster.} (17... Ne8 $5 {being ready to meet f2-f4 with
f7-f6.} 18. Qh3 Qc7 19. f4 Nd6 20. Rf3 {[%cal Gh3h5,Gf3h3] and White is either
blatantly attacking with a checkmate threat on h7, or provoking weaknesses
from Black. Engines always evaluate it cooly and announce equality.}) 18. f4 b4
19. f5 exf5 20. gxf5 bxc3 21. bxc3 Rac8 22. Qh3 Rc7 23. Re3 Rfc8 24. Rg3 $40 {
[%csl Rg7][%cal Gg1h1,Gf1g1] you'll notice this motif to appear more than once
- that's a nice idea to know.}) 13. Ne5 b5 {[%csl Rc5] a thematic approach but
this does weaken the c5 square - I suggest to try to exploit it.} 14. a3 {
stopping the immediate b5-b4 and there's no need for a flashy queen's
sacrifice!} (14. Bxb5 $5 a6 15. Bxc6 Rxb3 16. axb3 {this is definitely
interesting but I feel that only White can get in trouble here.} Bf5 17. b4 Ng4
18. Ba4 h5 19. h3 Nxe5 20. Rxe5 f6 21. Re3 e5 22. Nb3 Bc2 23. Ra1 h4 24. Nc5
Bxa4 25. Rxa4 exd4 26. cxd4 Qb6 27. b3 Ra8 28. Re7 Qd6 29. Rd7 Qc6 30. Rb7 Qd6
31. Rd7 Qc6 32. Rb7 Qe8 33. Ra1 Rb8 34. Rd7 Rd8 35. Rb7 Rb8 36. Rd7 Rd8 37. Rb7
{1/2-1/2 (37) Aronian,L (2767)-Mamedyarov,S (2801) Saint Louis 2018}) 14...
Rfc8 {Black stops Qc2 from happening.} (14... a5 15. Bxb5 Na7 16. a4 $14 {
is the key difference, why a2-a3 was so important to include.}) (14... Bh5 {
better later than never, at least for some clarity.} 15. Qc2 $1 $146 {[%cal
Gd2b3] I believe that White can get an advantage out of this position as Nb3 is
an incoming threat.} a5 16. Nb3 {[%cal Ge5c6,Gb3a5] threatening also with a
simple pawn grab!} a4 (16... b4 $4 {Black has no time to play this} 17. Nxc6
Qxc6 18. Nxa5 $18) 17. Nc1 Bg6 18. Bxg6 hxg6 19. Ncd3 $16 {[%cal Ge1e3,Ge3h3]
White returns to the simple plan. As Aleksandrs Koblencs once said about his
famous student Mikhail Tal: "If Misha has an open file, there will be a
checkmate".}) 15. Re3 (15. Qa2 $5 $146 {Since the c2 square is not available
because of the Nxd4 threat, there is another way to free up the b3 square for
the knight!} a5 16. Nb3 {[%cal Ge5c6,Gb3a5]} a4 17. Na1 $5 {[%cal Ga1c2] I
would pick here White without thinking.}) 15... Bh5 16. Rfe1 {and White is
keeping tabs on a7-a5, being ready to respond with Bxb5 and a3-a4. The engines
say that the position is about equal but it really depends if Black can push
a7-a5 and b5-b4.} a5 17. Bxb5 Na7 18. a4 Qb6 19. f3 $1 Nxb5 20. axb5 Qxb5 21.
Qxb5 Rxb5 22. b3 $14 {[%csl Ra5,Rh5] We've seen the arising idea already from
another line - the black bishop feels a little useless at h5.  I won't pretend
and announce that White gains an advantage in the main lines. I think they are
interesting, relatively unexplored and with the ideas, presented in the
database, you should have more chances than your opponent, especially if he's
unprepared. Happy hunting!} *

