1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. Bd3 Nf6 5. c3 Bg4 $5 {in the past few years
this continuation has had some extra popularity so I decided to include this
in my database as a separate chapter. I wasn't always able to find how to
transform the arising positions to already covered lines, so I had to dig a
little deeper.} (5... Nc6 6. Bf4 {transforms to chapters 6-9.}) 6. Qb3 {
[%csl Rb7] I suggest following the same approach as in Chapters 6-9. Since the
pawn on b7 at the moment is unprotected, we can try to win a tempo.} (6. Nf3 {
[%cal Rg4h5,Rh5g6] of course, White can always just play normal developing
moves but by doing so Black is facing no problems in the opening as the
light-squared bishop is quickly rerouted to g6.}) (6. Ne2 {This is playable
but the problem is that Black has saved up a tempo for Qc7 which I covered in
Chapter 5. Thus I wouldn't want to recommend something that is lesser than in
another chapter.} Nc6 7. O-O e6) 6... Qc7 {in my eyes, the only critical move
- other continuations don't really pose a problem.} (6... Qb6 $6 {Black
voluntarily accepts a slightly worse position.} 7. Qxb6 axb6 8. Na3 e6 (8...
Na6 9. Nb5 e6 10. Bf4 Be7 11. Ne2 Bxe2 12. Kxe2 $14 {1-0 (54) Kobalia,M (2614)
-Kuzubov,Y (2643) chess.com INT 2020}) 9. Nb5 Kd7 10. Ne2 $14 {[%csl Rg4][%cal
Ge2f4,Gh2h3]}) (6... Qc8 $6 {there have been some attempts to play this move,
but I don't really understand it. White can proceed with the same h2-h3 idea
and if Black would be willing to sacrifice a pawn on d5, the queen on c8 seems
to be simply misplaced.} 7. h3 (7. Bf4 Nc6 8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 {would transform
to the Chapter 8, but I think the new line is better.}) 7... Bd7 (7... Bf5 $2
8. Bxf5 Qxf5 9. Qxb7) (7... Bh5 8. g4 $1 $146 {to my great surprise, this is
an actual novelty! After 6...Qc7 this is the critical move with an unclear
position.} (8. Bf4 Nc6 9. Nd2 e6 10. Ngf3 Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. Rfe1 Bg6 13. Bxg6
hxg6 14. Ne5 Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Qc6 16. a4 Bd6 17. Nf3 Nd7 18. Bxd6 Qxd6 19. Re3
Rab8 20. Ne1 Nf6 21. Nd3 Ne4 22. Rae1 Qc7 23. Qd1 a6 24. h4 $14 {0-1 (41)
Eljanov, P (2672)-Hakobyan, A (2588) Lichess.org INT 2020}) 8... Bg6 9. Bxg6 hxg6
10. g5 Nfd7 {Black can never give any intermezzo checks on e6 as the pawn on
b7 will be left undefended, and the rook as well.} 11. Qxd5 $16 {I cannot
imagine how Qc8 is better than Qc7 in this line.}) 8. Bf4 Nc6 9. Nd2 $14 {
and Black is never going to be able to play Bf5 and Qxf5 as the pawn on b7 is
under attack.}) (6... Qd7 7. Bf4 Nc6 8. Nd2 e6 9. Ngf3 {would transform to
Chapter 9.}) 7. h3 {I wasn't able to find any other moves that could pose
problems for Black so I treat this move as the most critical continuation.} (7.
g3 $6 $146 {[%cal Gc1f4] I've tried to play this in several online blitz games
myself, and although I was never punished, it's a risky move if Black is up to
the task.} Nc6 8. Bf4 e5 $1 9. dxe5 Nxe5 (9... g5 $5 {engines love this move.})
10. Bb5+ Nfd7 11. Nd2 O-O-O {Black simply looks better because of the weakened
white king.}) (7. Ne2 {This is an alternative but I'm not satisfied that I'd
have to mix together two ideas - Qb3 and Ne2. As you already read in Chapters
4-6, the White queen would typically go to e1.} Nc6 8. Bf4 Qd7 9. O-O e6 10. Bg3
Be7 11. h3 Bf5 12. Bxf5 exf5 13. Nf4 O-O 14. Bh4 Rad8 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Nd3 Na5
17. Qc2 Nc4 18. Nd2 Rfe8 19. Rfe1 b6 20. Rad1 g6 $11 {1-0 (46) Praggnanandhaa,
R (2536)-Wei, Y (2736) chess.com INT 2019}) 7... Bd7 {If Black takes the
peaceful approach, we've managed to win a tempo by driving away the bishop
from a possible rerouting to g6 and can proceed with a positional game.} (7...
Bh5 $5 {Black accepts the challenge!} 8. g4 {the moment of truth - either it
works, or it doesn't! This is the start of a forced sequence after which White
wins a pawn by force.} Bg6 9. Bxg6 hxg6 10. g5 {[%csl Rd5]} Nfd7 (10... Nh5 $6
{the knight looks stuck here and is not contributing much to Black's
compensation for the pawn.} 11. Qxd5 Nc6 12. Nf3 e6 13. Qe4 Bd6 14. Be3 Ne7 15.
Nbd2 Nf5 16. O-O-O O-O 17. Kb1 $16 {1-0 (52) Abdusattorov,N (2627)-Sadhwani,R 
(2545) Lichess.org INT 2020}) 11. Qxd5 e5 12. Ne2 Nc6 13. Be3 {up to this
moment it's almost forced. Black has some sort of compensation for the pawn
but he has to prove it.} Nb6 (13... exd4 14. cxd4 Nb6 15. Qe4+ Qe7 16. Nbc3 Nb4
17. Qxe7+ Bxe7 18. O-O-O N4d5 19. h4 {There's a saying - a pawn is a pawn!})
14. Qf3 $5 {so far it's been played only once by the Russian GM Maksim Chigaev
in the 2019 World Rapid Chess Championship. The reason why I've chosen this
move over Qe4 is that it doesn't jump under the thematic f7-f5.} (14. Qe4 O-O-O
15. Nd2 f5 $1 (15... exd4 16. Nxd4 Nxd4 17. Bxd4 Bc5 18. Qg4+ Kb8 19. Bxc5 Qxc5
20. Qf4+ Ka8 21. O-O-O Nd5 22. Qf3 Nb4 23. Ne4 Qc4 24. b3 Qc6 25. Kb2 Nd5 26.
Rd4 Nb6 27. Rhd1 Rc8 28. Nd6 Qxf3 {0-1 (28) Predojevic,B (2601)-Postny,E (2600)
chess.com INT 2020}) 16. gxf6 gxf6 17. Qxg6 exd4 18. cxd4 (18. Nxd4 Nxd4 19.
Bxd4 Bh6 20. Be3 Bxe3 21. fxe3 Nd5 22. O-O-O Nxe3 23. Rde1 Qd6 24. Nc4 Nxc4 25.
Qg4+ Kb8 26. Qxc4 Rxh3 $11) 18... Nd5 $44 19. Rc1 Kb8 20. Qg3 Bd6 21. Qf3 Qf7
22. Ne4 Bc7 23. a3 Rhe8 24. N4c3 Nxe3 25. fxe3 Qb3 26. Kf2 f5 27. Rhd1 Rd7 28.
Rd2 Ne5 29. Qh5 Red8 30. Nf4 Nc4 31. Re2 Nxe3 32. Ng2 Nc4 33. Qf3 Rxd4 34. Kg1
Qb6 35. Qf2 Qd6 36. Ne1 Rg8+ 37. Kh1 Rf4 38. Nf3 Qh6 39. Rg1 Qxh3+ 40. Nh2 Rh8
41. Qe1 Qxh2+ 42. Rxh2 Rxh2+ 43. Kxh2 Rf2+ 44. Kh3 Rh2# {0-1 (44) Tukhaev,A 
(2542)-Mchedlishvili, M (2608) Ankara 2018}) 14... O-O-O {obviously from this
point on there's almost no games thus the practice will tell if this line will
be promising or not.} (14... exd4 $146 15. Nxd4 Nxd4 16. Bxd4 O-O-O 17. Nd2 $14
) 15. Nd2 exd4 (15... Kb8 $146 {White can't long castle yet so he needs to
prepare it first. If Black doesn't play Kb8, at the right time White might
play Qg4+ to improve the coordination of his pieces and eye for a potential
lash out of Na4.} 16. Ne4 {[%cal Ge1c1] with a long castle incoming - the pawn
on d4 will be extra protected by the rook.} f5 17. gxf6 gxf6 18. O-O-O $14) (
15... Na4 $2 16. Qg4+ ({or} 16. d5 Ne7 17. Qg4+ Qd7 18. Qxd7+ Kxd7 19. b3 Nb2
20. c4 $16) 16... Kb8 17. d5 {[%csl Ra4] Can unexpectedly drop a piece!}) 16.
Nxd4 Nxd4 17. Bxd4 Bc5 18. Bxc5 Qxc5 19. O-O-O Qxg5 20. Qxf7 Rd6 21. h4 Rxh4
22. Rxh4 Qxh4 23. Re1 $16 {1/2-1/2 (51) Chigaev,M (2631)-Rozum,I (2573) Moscow
2019}) 8. Nf3 e6 (8... g6 9. Bg5 {Black could have problems defending the d5
pawn.}) 9. O-O Bd6 10. Re1 Bc6 {[%cal Rf6e4,Rb8d7] this idea was first played
in a correspondence game back in 2013 between Steinkellner and Tyulenko. Black
is ready to counter-strike back with a timely executed Nf6-e4.} (10... Nc6 $6 {
looks too passive} 11. Qd1 Ng8 12. Nbd2 Nge7 13. a3 (13. Nf1 O-O-O 14. b3 f6
15. c4 Bf4 16. Bd2 Bxd2 17. Qxd2 {1/2-1/2 (56) Kurajica,B (2525)-Olafsson,F
Amsterdam 1976}) 13... a6 14. c4 $5 {[%cal Gb2b3,Gc1b2] is an interesting
change of the character of the position.}) 11. Qd1 $1 {[%cal Gd1e2] the white
queen is rerouted to e2 to control the e5 square as on b3 it has nothing to do
anymore.} (11. Ne5 Nbd7 12. Bf4 (12. f4 $5 $13 {[%csl Re4] the engines say
that this is playable, however with immediate access for Black to the
weakened e4 square, I'm a little cautious about this approach.}) 12... Ne4 {
probably doesn't bring White the desired results}) 11... Nbd7 12. Qe2 {[%cal
Gf3e5,Gc1f4] White's plan is simple - manage to play Nf3-e5 and Bf4. If you
manage to do that, White is solidly better.} O-O 13. Ne5 {I suggest to stick
to the only game in this line so far - the correspondence game back in 2013.} (
13. Nbd2 {[%cal Gf3e5,Gd2f3] This was Ganguly's attempt to improve the
variation in 2020 - White is threatening with Nf3-e5 and position the 2nd
knight to f3.} Nh5 $1 {[%cal Rh5f4] quite a critical response - Black is not
afraid of the thematical Bxh7 sacrifice! The arising variations can be very
complex but the engines insist that Black is holding. Ganguly went for the
most critical lines with guns blazing, but you don't have to unless you've
backed it with some very deep analysis.} (13... Rfe8 14. Ne5 {it can be quite
difficult for Black to come up with the next move.} Rad8 15. Ndf3 $14 {[%cal
Gc1f4]}) 14. Nf1 {this leads to some very interesting positions.} (14. Bxh7+ $5
{The position becomes incredibly complex and the engines insist that this is a
draw...} Kxh7 15. Ng5+ Kg6 (15... Kh6 16. Ndf3 Nf4 17. Qe3 g6 18. g3 Kg7 19.
gxf4 Rae8 $13) 16. Ndf3 Nf4 17. Qc2+ Kf6 18. g3 Ng6 19. Nxf7 Kxf7 20. Ng5+ Kg8
21. Qxg6 Nf6 22. Nxe6 Qd7 23. Bh6 Ne4 24. Rxe4 dxe4 25. Ng5 Rf7 26. Qh7+ (26.
Nxf7 Qxf7 27. Qxd6 gxh6 28. Qxh6 Rf8 29. Qg5+ {and probably the game would end
with a perpetual check unless Black wants to play with a bishop against 4
white pawns.}) 26... Kf8 27. Nxf7 Qxf7 28. d5 Qxd5 29. Qxg7+ Ke8 30. Qg6+ Kd7
31. Qg7+ Ke8 32. Qg6+ Kd7 33. Qg7+ Be7 34. c4 Qf5 35. b4 Ke6 36. Rd1 Bf6 37.
Rd6+ Kxd6 38. Qf7 Bd7 39. Bf4+ Kc6 40. b5+ Kc5 {0-1 (40) Ganguly,S (2636)
-Eljanov,P (2650) Wijk aan Zee 2020}) (14. g3 $2 Bxg3 15. fxg3 Qxg3+ 16. Kh1
Nf4 17. Qf1 Nxd3 18. Qxd3 Qxh3+ 19. Kg1 Qg3+ 20. Kh1 e5 $1 {[%cal Rc6h1] Black
is taking over}) 14... Nf4 15. Bxf4 {Unfortunately White has to give away his
dark-squared bishop.} Bxf4 16. g3 Bd6 17. Ne3 {from here on the game obviously
is not forced but let me illustrate to you a possible continuation} (17. N1h2
Rfe8 18. Ng4 f6 19. Qc2 Nf8 {[%cal Re6e5] it seems that Black is doing
excellent here and is ready to fire away with e6-e5 and it's not clear what
the white knight is doing on g4.}) 17... Rfe8 18. Rad1 f6 19. Qc2 Nf8 20. Kg2
Rad8 21. h4 {with an interesting game, for example} Kh8 (21... e5 $6 22. dxe5
fxe5 23. Qb3 {[%csl Rg8][%cal Gd3e4,Gb3g8]}) 22. h5 e5 23. Nh4 $13 {This
particular position I'd choose White.}) 13... Bxe5 {the critical move} 14. dxe5
Ne4 {and Black has various possibilities to sacrifice the knight on e4 for at
least two pawns and a strong centre.} 15. Bc2 $5 (15. f3 $146 {this direct
move almost forces Black to sacrifice the piece.} Nxe5 (15... Ng3 $6 16. Qf2
Nh5 17. g4 Nxe5 18. Rxe5 Qxe5 19. f4 $1 $16 {[%cal Gg4h5]}) (15... f5 $5 $13)
16. fxe4 Nxd3 17. Qxd3 dxe4 {[%cal Rf7f3] The game is very complex and for the
sake of some clarity probably it's a good idea to return some of the material.
If played out perfectly from both sides, it should end with a draw.} 18. Rxe4 (
18. Qf1 f5 19. Nd2 Rad8 {looks too scary to play for White}) 18... Qb6+ 19. Kh2
Bxe4 20. Qxe4 Qd6+ 21. Qf4 e5 22. Qf1 f5 23. c4 f4 24. Nc3 Qd4 25. Nb5 Qb6 26.
b3 a6 27. Nc3 Qd4 28. Bb2 Qd2 29. Qc1 {[%cal Gc3d5]} (29. Qe2 $6 Rad8 30. Re1
$4 {unfortunately loses to} f3 31. gxf3 Qf4+ 32. Kh1 Rd2) 29... Qf2 30. Ne4 Qe2
31. Nc3 Qf2 32. Ne4 $11) 15... Nxe5 $5 {This is the suggested continuation in
Francesco Rambaldi's book "The Revisited Caro-Kann", which was released in
2020.} (15... f5 16. a4 Rac8 17. Na3 a6 18. Bf4 Qd8 19. f3 Qh4 20. Be3 f4 21.
Bd4 Ng3 22. Qf2 $13 Rf7 23. Rac1 g5 24. c4 Rcf8 25. Bb3 dxc4 26. Nxc4 Bd5 27.
Rc3 Rg7 28. Nd6 Bxb3 29. Rxb3 h5 30. Kh2 g4 31. Ne4 Qd8 32. fxg4 hxg4 33. Nf6+
Nxf6 34. exf6 Nf5 35. fxg7 g3+ 36. Kh1 gxf2 37. gxf8=Q+ Kxf8 38. Bc5+ Ke8 39.
Bxf2 Qd2 40. Rxb7 Nd4 41. Re5 {I am sure it's possible to include this game
somewhere along the way} Qxf2 {1/2-1/2 (41) Steinkellner, P (2304)-Tyulenko, Y 
(2452) ICCF email 2013}) 16. Bf4 (16. f3 $6 {unfortunately has a nice
refutation by the means of} Bb5 $1 17. Qxb5 $4 Nxf3+ 18. Kf1 Qh2 {and White is
crushed.}) 16... f6 17. Nd2 Qb6 18. Bxe5 fxe5 19. Bxe4 $1 {My suggested
improvement which is not mentioned in the book. The knight will be superior to
the bishop!} (19. Nxe4 {is also playable but perhaps with much more drawish
tendencies. After} dxe4 20. Rab1 Rf4 {Rambaldi gives here equality but I'm
not sure it's so simple from a practical point of view} 21. Qe3 Qxe3 22. Rxe3 {
if White will manage to recapture the pawn on e4, pretty much every single
endgame will be slightly better for him.} Raf8 (22... Rd8 23. Rd1 Rxd1+ (23...
Rff8 24. Kf1 Bb5+ 25. Ke1 Rxd1+ 26. Bxd1 Bd3 27. Be2 Bb1 28. c4 {[%cal Ge3a3,
Ga3b3,Ge2g4,Ge1d2,Gd2e3]}) 24. Bxd1 Kf8 25. g3 Rf7 26. Kf1 Ke7 27. Ke1 Kd6 (
27... h6 28. Bc2 Rf3 29. Rxf3 exf3 30. Kd2 $14 {[%cal Gd2e3]}) 28. Bc2) 23. Re2
Rd8 24. b3 {[%cal Gb1e1,Gc2e4]}) 19... dxe4 20. Nc4 Qc7 21. Ne3 {[%csl Ge3,Re4,
Re5,Re6] White has nicely blocked the triple pawns and can pressure Black
indefinitely.} Rf4 22. Rad1 Raf8 {[%csl Rc6]} 23. Rf1 $14 {[%cal Gd1d2,Gb2b3,
Gc3c4] I think Black still needs to prove that he can hold this. Notice how
passive is the black bishop on c6.} *

