{[%evp 0,7,24,44,71,44,86,79,87,87] [#]} {Black has voluntarily went for a
position with an isolated queen's pawn on d5 but with a good development. What
is the best plan here for White?} 13. Re1 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gc1e3] The right
answer is - play for a light-piece blockade on d4, typically a knight. Trading
the dark-squared bishops will diminish Black's chances for an initiative at
the kingside.} (13. Be3 $6 {would create a weakness on e3 which nullifies the
effect of the isolated pawn on d5.} Bxe3 14. fxe3 Bf5 $11) 13... h6 {a
necessary move} (13... Bg4 $4 {immediately doesn't work because of a simple
tactic.} 14. Bxh7+ Kxh7 15. Ng5+) 14. Be3 Bc7 {[%cal Rd8d6,Rc7h2] of course,
Black would like to keep the prospects for a kingside attack, making a battery
of the bishop and a queen.} 15. h3 {stopping Bg4 for good.} Bf5 16. Bc5 $14 {
[%cal Gb3d4] by now it should become apparent that Black has no attack at the
kingside and that the pawn on d5 is just a weakness.} *

