{[%evp 0,11,34,-6,64,-17,20,-7,10,-12,8,6,6,-4] [#]} {Black has just
positioned his dark-squared bishop on a much more active square of c5 instead
of the more modest e7 - how should you exploit this to your advantage?} 10. Bg5
{[%cal Gg5f6,Gd1d5] threatening with Bxf6 and Qxd5.} (10. Re1+ $6 Be6 11. Ng5
$2 {is tempting but it just doesn't work as it has a direct refutation, plus
Black can always sacrifice the pawn on e6 for a very dangerous initiative.}
Bxf2+ (11... O-O {also looks great for Black.} 12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. Rxe6 Ne4 $19)
12. Kxf2 Qb6+) 10... Be6 11. Nd4 Rc8 12. Bxc6+ bxc6 13. Qe2 Qe7 (13... Bxd4 14.
cxd4 O-O 15. Nc3 $14) 14. Re1 O-O 15. Nd2 $14 {[%cal Ge2f3] this sequence is
more or less forced - White is definitely pushing.} *

