{[%evp 0,3,4,-7,0,2] [#]} {Black has just played f7-f6 - what is he planning?} 
13. Qc2 $1 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Rd7e8,Re8g6] While the e6-e5 breakthrough seems to
be the obvious answer, you should pay more attention for Bd7-e8-g6, exchanging
the bad bishop. This little manoeuvre stops this idea for good. If Black will
push e6-e5, this will leave him with an isolated queens pawn.} (13. Qd2 $6 Be8
$11 {[%cal Re8g6]}) 13... g6 {after this you can reroute the queen wherever
you feel it's contributing something to the position.} (13... h6 {if Black
does this, then he can't play Be8-g6 anymore thus it's advised to keep the
queen on c2 for the time being.} 14. Rae1 Rac8 {[%cal Rc6b4]} 15. a3) 14. Qd2 {
[%cal Re6e5,Gb2b3,Gc3c4] with a long and strategic battle. White should keep
an eye for the thematic e6-e5 and prepare himself b2-b3 and c3-c4.} *

